<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 25 Injured in Police-Traders Clash in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Some 25 people were injured as
angry traders, protesting against the government's plan to expand
tax net, Wednesday clashed with riot police in Rawalpindi, twin
city of Islamabad, a local trader said.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested several dozens of traders during the five-hour
protest at the center of the city, according to Hanif Abbasi,
chairman of a local trader organization, Tajir Action Committee.
</P>
<P>
Police fired tear gas and used batons to disperse the
procession of around 2,000 traders, Abbasi said.
</P>
<P>
The clash started when some demonstrators pelted stone at
several shops which were open in Raja Bazzar, a downtown market.
</P>
<P>
The traders also burnt tires and threw stones at the police,
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
The protest took place after the longest strike of traders last
month against the tax survey by the military government which
intended to bring more businessmen under the tax net through the
survey.
</P>
<P>
Though the government has started collecting the survey forms,
traders are still divided over the new procedure. Traders in
Multan of Punjab province and Peshawar of Northwest Frontier
Province had also clashed with the police.
</P>
<P>
Despite the protest, the government is determined to go ahead
with its plan to expand the tax net. According to the Central
Board of Revenue, over 400,000 tax survey forms have been
distributed, of which roughly 90,000 have been collected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
