<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Three-Way Mideast Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
announced on Wednesday that he will convene a summit with Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat at
Camp, Maryland, early next week to deal with difficult core issues
on the Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
"Early next week, Prime Minister Barak and Chairman Arafat will
come to Camp David at my invitation,... The objective is to reach
an agreement on the core issues that have fueled a half-century of
conflict between Israelis and Palestinians," Clinton said in the
White House briefing room.
</P>
<P>
He said there are "no easy answers, and certainly no painless
ones" and "clearly no guarantee of success".
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that Israeli and Palestinian negotiators will
arrive in advance to help pave the way for this summit.
</P>
<P>
Clinton did not provide a specific date for the summit but
earlier reports quoted senior U.S. officials as saying that the
summit will commence on July 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
