<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's exports volume stood at 1.137 billion U.S.
dollars in the first quarter of this year, up by 31.4 percent from
780 million dollars during the same period of last year, said a
report compiled by the trade representation offices affiliated to
the Egyptian Ministry of Economy and Foreign Trade.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's exports included unconventional, industrial and non-oil
products such as ceramics, marble, granite, building materials,
engineering and mining facilities, chemicals, aluminium products,
iron and steel.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish Treasury said on Thursday that the
country's total external debts reached 103.474 billion U.S. dollars
as of March 31, 2000, reported Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, an increase of 1.7 billion
dollars in the external debts was registered.
</P>
<P>
As of the first three months of this year, the short-term share
in the total debts was 23.80 percent and the medium- and long-term
share was 76.20 percent.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's cotton exports volume hit 105,200 tons in the
current marketing season of 1999-2000 which ended on June 24, down
by 5 percent from 110,633 tons in the previous season of 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
Cotton exports fetched 221.214 million U.S. dollars to the
Treasury.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's trade deficits stood at 8 billion Egyptian
pounds (2.3 billion U.S. dollars)in the first quarter of this year,
down by 46.67 percent from 15 billion pounds (4.3 billion dollars)
during the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The volume of bank deposits increased to 250 billion pounds (72
billion dollars) at the end of last March from 230 billion pounds
(66.28 billion dollars) during the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The rate of inflation dropped to 2.9 percent per annum for the
first time in six years, while it dived to 0.2 percent last April.
</P>
<P>
The volume of exports hit more than 3.872 billion pounds (1.2
billion dollars) during the period from January to March, up by 30.
27 percent from 2.7 billion pounds (778.1 million dollars) during
the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the volume of imports nosedived to 11.918 billion
pounds (3.4 billion dollars), a decline of 2 million pounds (576,
369 dollars). 
</P>
