<HEADLINE> Cuba to Keep Stance on Migration Dialog with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Cuba's government said Thursday it'
ll keep unchanged its stance on migration talks with the United
States, whose last round should have taken place in New York at
the end of June.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Aymee Hernandez said that
both countries will return to talks on matters such as the Cuban
Adjustment Act, which grants automatic residence to Cubans
arriving on U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
Hernandez also mentioned among these discrepancies human
contraband that's promoted from the United States by Florida radio
stations that promote illegal immigration on the island.
</P>
<P>
Cuba and the United States, which have no diplomatic relations,
signed in 1994 and ratified in 1995 an accord to regulate, order
and legalize migratory flux toward American land.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1994 and 1995 immigration accords, 20,000 Cubans are
allowed to immigrate to the United States legally.
</P>
<P>
In line with those accords, Cubans trying to enter the United
States illegally who are intercepted at sea must be returned to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
But unlike other illegal immigrants, Cubans who manage to evade
the Coast Guard and reach U.S. shores are allowed to seek legal
residency and work permits under a U.S. law passed in 1966.
</P>
</TEXT>
