<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Council Urges Afghan Parties to Resume Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council Thursday urged the warring parties in Afghanistan,
particular the Taliban, to resume negotiations under United
Nations auspices without further delay and any preconditions.
</P>
<P>
The move came when the 15-member Security Council was briefed
by Under-Secretary-General Kieran Prendergast on the latest
situation in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council expressed concern at the resumption of
major hostilities on July 1, 2000 and warned the parties not to
undertake new attempts to pursue a military solution to the
conflict in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council reiterated its call to all Afghan parties
to work together for peace and the establishment of a broad-based,
multiethnic and fully representative government.
</P>
<P>
The Council expressed its serious concern about the plight of
the Afghan people suffering from the continuing war, including
summary executions of prisoners and shelling of civilian populated
areas, which adds to the severe humanitarian situation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Council insists that all parties take responsibility for
the safety and the security of the civilian population and of
humanitarian personnel in areas of Afghanistan under their control
as well as in areas of conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Council also expressed its concern at the restrictions
imposed on the work of humanitarian organizations and urged all
parties to facilitate the delivery of humanitarian aid to all
those in need.
</P>
<P>
The Council reiterated its serious concern at the continuing
use of the Afghan territory, especially under control of the
Taliban, for the support to the international terrorist activities
and production and trafficking of illicit drug, as well as serious
violations of human rights, in particular, those of women and
girls.
</P>
<P>
The Council reiterated that continuing disregard by the
Taliban of the demands made in relevant U.N. resolutions was
totally unacceptable and confirmed its determination to ensure
full compliance by the Taliban without conditions with its
obligations.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban controls about 90 percent of Afghanistan and a
north-based opposition alliance resisting it holds the remaining
10 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
