<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Zone Industrial Producer Prices Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The euro zone industrial producer
price index was 0.8 percent higher in May compared to April,
European Union (EU) statistical office, Eurostat, reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The index had edged up by 0.1 percent in April. The 0.8 percent
increase was the highest since July 1999.
</P>
<P>
The May increase stems from the intermediate goods sector which
advanced 1.2 percent in the euro zone. The 11 euro zone countries
are Belgium, Germany, Spain, France, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg,
the Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and Finland. Britain, Sweden,
Denmark and Greece are now outside the euro area.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prices in the whole EU region (EU) were
unchanged in April and increased 0.7 percent in May. The rise was
also the highest since July 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the Eurostat, France and Finland recorded both an
increase of 1.3 percent in May and prices were 0.9 percent higher
in both Italy and the Netherlands. Producer Prices in Spain (0.4
percent) and Germany (0.6 percent) advanced less than the 15-
nation EU average and the index was unchanged in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The available data shows that producer prices continued to
increase on an annual basis. They were up by 6.5 percent in the
euro zone and 5.7 percent in EU compared to May 1999.
</P>
<P>
The rise in April had been 5.8 percent in the euro zone and 5.1
percent in the EU. The increase stems again mainly from the
intermediate goods sector, where the index was 10.9 percent and 9.
9 percent higher in the euro zone and in the EU15 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The index shows changes in capital goods and durable consumer
goods were below one percent. The index for non-durable consumer
goods was 1.4 percent higher in the euro zone and 1.3 percent in
the EU15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
