<HEADLINE> Tanzania, Burundi Agree to Strengthen Consultation on Border Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Burundi have
agreed to strengthen their bilateral consultations at military and
administrative level to ensure peace and security along their
common border.
</P>
<P>
In a consultative meeting held here Thursday, the Tanzanian
Minister of Defense and National Service Edgar Majogo and his
Burundian counterpart Cyrille Ndayirukiye agreed to coordinate in
advance any impending operations to be taken by either side along
the common border.
</P>
<P>
The 11-man Burundian armed forces delegation arrived here on
Wednesday for a three-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two ministers also reviewed the
security situation along the common border and recalled some of
the causes of insecurity, such as the persistence of the crisis in
Burundi and the existence of some criminal elements within the
Burundian refugee camps in western Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that some of the causes of insecurity along the
common border can be resolved if the Burundi Peace Negotiations
under the facilitation of former South African president Nelson
Mandela will be finalized at the earliest date.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers requested the negotiating parties to speed up
the process in order to allow the agreement to be signed.
</P>
<P>
"We request the negotiating parties to speed up the process in
order to allow the agreement to be signed so as to restore peace
and calm, law and order, which are vital for the political, social
and economic development of Burundi," the visiting defense
minister said. 
</P>
