<HEADLINE> Ethiopia PM Hails Performance in Last Fiscal Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian government has
done a good job during the just-ending fiscal year, Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a report presented to the 24th regular meeting of the
Council of Peoples' Representatives, Meles said his cabinet has
successfully accomplished the three set tasks, namely the defense
of the country's sovereignty, fighting the drought and holding
national elections.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that the restoration of the country's
sovereignty has led to a stage where border demarcation is about
to start based on international law and border treaties.
</P>
<P>
The restoration of Ethiopian sovereignty refers to the latest
round of its border conflict with Eritrea in May, during which
Ethiopia claimed to have recaptured all its territories occupied
since May 1998.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the drought situation, Meles said the natural
disaster has caused great losses to human lives in spite of
concerted efforts made at all levels alongside the national
defense effort.
</P>
<P>
Meles said that real casualties have been considerably reduced
as a result of the prompt action taken by the Ethiopian government
to purchase food from domestic markets for distribution among
drought victims.
</P>
<P>
He complained that the international community had not provided
 satisfactory response to appeal for humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that as the people volunteered to carry
the burden of the war, no problem had occurred in inflationary
trends or in fluctuation of foreign currency market. As to the
May 14 national elections, Meles said the elections was carried
out successfully in all parts of the country with the exception of
the re-election held in the Southern Nations, Nationalities and
Peoples State due to some electoral irregularities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
