<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increasing Elders to Burden African Social Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Social security schemes in
sub-Saharan African countries stand to face a heavy burden between
now and the year 2020 when the proportion of elderly population in
the region is expected to double.
</P>
<P>
Eyitayo Lambo, managing director of the International
Management and Health Consultants, sounded the warning here
Thursday when speaking at a meeting of directors of social
security organizations in English-speaking Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said demographic trends have very important repercussions on
social security schemes and that an increase in aged population,
which in the past was not considered a major task for Africa, is
becoming an issue of concern.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the problems could be solved through
increasing the revenues into the systems by generating additional
revenue through the extension of coverage and increasing taxable
earnings under social security.
</P>
<P>
Social security's costs are driven by demographic and economic
trends that influence the relative size of the worker and
beneficiary populations and the average benefit payment.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, given the demographic projections, it is
clear that social security administrators should be wary of the
impact of the demographic changes on the financing of social
security schemes.
</P>
<P>
He mentioned the major demographic changes and projections in
the sub- Saharan region as higher fertility rate, increased infant
mortality and adult mortality rates, a drastic drop of life
expectancy at birth in countries hardest hit by HIV/AIDS and a
remarkable increase in life expectancy among the aged population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE to Launch WAP Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 6 (Xinhua)-- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
Telecommunications Corporation (Etisalat) will launch Wireless
Application Protocol (WAP) services within two months, to give
mobile phone users access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Emirates' official WAM news agency said on Thursday that the WAP

services will be provided in two months, with a portal that will
run in both Arabic and English.
</P>
<P>
Etisalat's WAP service will be the first in the region,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"All phones in the UAE will soon be WAP-enabled to enable mobile
phone users to surf the web," the report said.
</P>
<P>
WAP is a global specification that empowers mobile users with
wireless devices to easily access and interact with information and
services.
</P>
<P>
Apart from access to the Internet and checking and sending e-
mails, WAP services can also provide message notification and call
management, mapping and locator services, weather and traffic
alerts, news, sports and information services, e-commerce
transactions, banking services, online address books, directory
services and corporate Internet applications, said the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
