<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Earns Over 1 Bln Dlrs In June Through Oil-For-Food Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraq earned some 282 million
U.S. dollars in the last week of June from exporting over 10
million barrels of oil, the figures of the United Nations Office
of the Iraq Program said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Since the program's current six-month period, or "Phase VIII,"
began on June 9, Iraq has earned an estimated 1.068 billion
dollars, the office said.
</P>
<P>
Overall, since the program began in December 1996, Iraq has
exported more than 1.871 billion barrels of oil valued at more
than 30 billion dollars, according to the office.
</P>
<P>
Equipment for the oil industry and humanitarian supplies,
including almost 82,000 tons of wheat, as well as infant formula
and school furniture, continued to arrive normally through the
three land border points and the Iraqi port of Umm Qasr, the
office said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since its invasion of Kuwait
in 1990. The oil-for-food program began to be implemented in late
1996, aiming to ease the suffering of the Iraqi people caused by
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions cannot be lifted until the United Nations
notifies that Iraq has destroyed all its weapons of mass
destruction. U.N. arms inspectors have not returned to the country
since the U.S-led military strikes in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Office of the Iraq Program administers the U.
N. humanitarian program known as oil-for-food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
