<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Book Reveals Root Causes of Biodiversity Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF)
released Thursday a wake-up-call book, "Root Causes of
Biodiversity Loss," the first study ever to provide a
comprehensive overview of the driving forces behind the loss of
biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
Based on case studies conducted in Brazil, Cameroon, China,
Danube Basin, India, Mexico, Pakistan, the Philippines, Tanzania
and Vietnam, the book developed an analytical approach to
understanding the root causes of biodiversity loss and applied it
to varying situations and countries.
</P>
<P>
The study identified the root causes of biodiversity loss as
being factors such as population growth, poverty, international
trade, macroeconomic policies and poor environmental law or weak
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
As the book observed, the world is losing species and
biodiversity at a rate unprecedented in history. The causes go
deep, and the losses are driven by a complex array of social,
economic, political and biological factors at different levels.
Immediate causes, such as over-harvesting, pollution and habitat
change, have been well studied. But the socioeconomic factors
driving people to degrade their environment are less well
understood.
</P>
<P>
The book, published by Earthscan, examined the underlying
causes. It provided analyses of the 10 case studies around the
world and integrated them into a new and interdisciplinary
framework for understanding what is happening.
</P>
<P>
From these results, Alexander Wood, Pamela Stedman-Edwards and
Johanna Mang, editors of the book, were able to derive policy
conclusions and recommendations for operational and institutional
approaches to address the root causes and reverse the current
trends.
</P>
<P>
While releasing the book, WWF, the conservation organization,
warned governments and international organizations that action at
local level is not enough to prevent biodiversity loss, and called
on them to take into account the global forces behind
environmental degradation when designing development policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N., Cambodia End Talks on Khmer Rouge Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations said
Thursday that the talks between the U.N. and Cambodia on the trial
of former Khmer Rouge leaders had concluded.
</P>
<P>
The talks were conducted between Hans Corell, U.N. legal
counsel, and Sok An, Cambodia's chief negotiator and chairman of
the Council of Ministers.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the U.N. spokesman's office said Hans
Corell had completed formal discussions with the Royal Government
of Cambodia on the establishment of a tribunal to try Khmer Rouge
leaders early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal envisaged would be a Cambodian court with the
participation of international judges and prosecutors, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Because the outstanding substantive issues were resolved by the
U.N. secretary-general and the Cambodian prime minister, the
discussions focused on technical issues involved in forming the
tribunal, and were frank and comprehensive, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Corell provided his Cambodian counterpart, Sok An, with a draft
Memorandum of Understanding that would govern the relationship
between Cambodia and the United Nations, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Memorandum of the Understanding would be singed by the
United Nations and Cambodia after the Cambodian parliament passes
legislation that is in keeping with the understanding between the
parties, it said.
</P>
<P>
As Corell and Sok An agreed at a post meeting press conference,
the responsibility for moving the process toward completion now
lies squarely with the government of Cambodia, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations ended after four rounds of talks since the U.N.
team arrived in Cambodia Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Corell had five rounds of talks in Phnom Penh in March, leaving
then without resolving conflicts over the right of a foreign
prosecutor to indict suspects.
</P>
<P>
That hurdle was worked out between U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan and Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen before Corell and his
team returned to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has been involved in getting a trial set up
since 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
