<HEADLINE> Air Pollution Causes as Many Deaths As Road Accidents in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The death toll through air
pollution was comparable to that for road accidents in Greece, the
Greenpeace said in a report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Describing the current situation in Greece as not tolerable,
the Greek bureau of the environmental organization said that it
estimated the social costs at 548 million drachmas (about 1.6
million U.S. dollars) in the short term and 2,096 billion drachmas
(about 595 million dollars) in the long term.
</P>
<P>
Attributing air pollution mainly to cars, the Greenpeace
called for measures be taken to deal with this problem, such as
the increasing use of non-pollution trams, railways and renewable
energy sources as well as the protection and development of
forests around cities.
</P>
<P>
Greece is the only EU member state in which the number of road
accidents is steadily increasing instead of decreasing.
</P>
<P>
Greece's traffic accident rate is among the highest in the 15-
member EU countries, with nearly 3,000 people killed and 30,000
others injured annually in accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
