<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Criticizes Foreign Interference in Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The newly concluded parliamentary
election was not only a fight between the ruling party and local
opposition parties but also with foreign enemies, said Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing members of the Political Bureau and new Members of
Parliament of the ruling Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic
Front (ZANU-PF), Mugabe said the greatest opposition during the
June 24-25 election was that of Britain.
</P>
<P>
"We were not dealing with a local enemy, but a foreign one," he
said, noting that "the totality of the weaponry of the British,
all newspapers, all televisions, all of them were mobilized to
fight us."
</P>
<P>
According to the president, the British sought support from
Europe and America for the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC) to
beat ZANU-PF.
</P>
<P>
MDC was a mere shadow or agency of greater opposition from
Britain and it was a mammoth task for ZANU-PF to win in these
circumstances, he said.
</P>
<P>
"To have achieved a historic victory, this must go down as a
very precious win," he told the parliamentarians, stressing that
this "natural act of success" has saved the party from extinction.
</P>
<P>
The president also noted that his party had not done well
partly because membership at the grassroots was not cohesive and
the party had to appeal to traditional leaders to win support in
areas where structures were disorganized.
</P>
<P>
He urged party members to understand the party's strengths and
weaknesses so that they could build on them to overcome problems.
</P>
<P>
In the country's fifth parliamentary election, ZANU-PF won 62
of the 120 contested seats while MDC gained 57 and ZANU (Ndonga)
one. 
</P>
