<HEADLINE> Britain Vows to Support Angola's Peace Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Kingdom and other members
of the European Union (EU) Thursday pledged support for the
Angolan government's effort to bring peace and democracy to the
war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech at University of Agostinho Neto in the
Angolan capital Luanda, British Foreign Office Minister for
African Affairs Peter Hain said that the EU hope peace would come
in Angola as soon as possible so that the Angolan citizens can
live decent lives.
</P>
<P>
Describing the 26-year civil war between the government troops
and the rebel National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) as "so long and so painful", Hain said that the world will
not continue to tolerate rebel leader Jonas Savimbi's lies and
obstructions.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA should have its voice heard through the votes in
ballot boxes but not the gun barrels, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Britain is committed to the implementation of the U.N.
 sanctions against UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
"We want to impede them from selling diamonds and block their
supplies of fuel and munitions until they are obliged to lay down
their arms," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hain is currently in Angola for a two-day visit. He has met
with Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and Foreign
Minister Joao Miranda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
