<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disasters Blamed for Worsening Poverty in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Vice Chancellor of Africa University
Rukudzo Murapa Thursday blamed both man-made and natural
disasters for worsening poverty and suffering of people in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening a two-week workshop on leadership,
communication and management skills at the university near Mutare
of east Zimbabwe, Murapa said "we are concerned that natural and
man-made disasters are a force in the perpetuation of poverty in
Africa."
</P>
<P>
He singled out cyclone Eline floods as one of the natural
disasters which hit five African countries without warning.
</P>
<P>
Africa should be equipped with relevant preparedness and
emergency rescue skills to react promptly against such disasters
and serve life, he said.
</P>
<P>
The cyclone Eline which was experienced in February and March
this year in Botswana, Madagascar, Mozambique, South Africa and
Zimbabwe has caused serious damage to economic infrastructure and
claimed many lives.
</P>
<P>
Murapa also noted that the bloody civil wars in many countries
on the continent continue to wreak havoc and cause untold human
suffering.
</P>
<P>
According to the vice chancellor, the board of directors in
Africa University has agreed to establish an Institute for Peace
and Governance where issues related to disaster management will
remain central in the proposed curriculum.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, which was attended by 25 field officers from non-
governmental and state organizations from 13 African countries,
seeks to train participants in emergency rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
The participants are expected to hold similar workshops and
train people in their home countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
