<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Beefs Up Efforts to Develop Water Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia, traditionally
depending on natural rainfall for its agricultural production, has
begun to attach importance to the development of water projects in
the country, Ethiopian News Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Water Resources Development was quoted as
saying that it had undertaken the feasibility study and design
works of nine water projects with an outlay of nearly 95 million
birr (1.1 million U.S. dollars) during 1999/2000 fiscal year that
ends on July 7.
</P>
<P>
Gulilat Birhane, a senior official with the ministry, said that
the water projects include study and design on small-scale
irrigation schemes, medium-scale hydropower generation, surface
water development as well as construction of buildings for
meteorological services.
</P>
<P>
A network of meteorological services will be established at a
cost of 17 million birr (about two million U.S. dollars) in
various parts of the country, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia is nicknamed "Water tower of East Africa" for its
plentiful of water resources resulted from rainfall. However, the
Horn of Africa country suffered a lot from drought due to uneven
rainfall in the country in last three years.
</P>
<P>
Some 10 million Ethiopian people, mainly living in the rural
and pastoral areas, were reportedly facing starvation after
their homeland was subjected to successive years of drought.
</P>
<P>
To change the condition of living off rainfall, the Ethiopian
government is determined to take measures to construct as many as
possible man-made water irrigation system to guarantee
agricultural production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
