<HEADLINE> Zambia Has 700,000 Orphan Population: UNCEF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has an estimated 700,000
orphans and vulnerable children population, according to the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
UNICEF Resident Representative Peter McDermott told a workshop
which opened here Thursday that Zambia had a large population of
orphans and vulnerable children due to the combined effects of
HIV/AIDS and high levels of poverty, although the country enjoys
relative peace compared with other countries on the African
continent.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that over 75 percent of Zambians live in
abject poverty, while one in every five persons in the country is
HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
McDermott said that if the trend did not change the population
of orphans in Zambia and other countries in the region would
collectively reach 11 million by the year 2010, a situation he
described as disastrous to mankind.
</P>
<P>
McDermott took a swipe at developed nations, criticizing that
they concentrated their efforts and committed billions of U.S.
dollars on the research in animal sciences rather than helping
poor African countries fight the AIDS pandemic, which had
devastated the continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
