<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi Facing Serious Unemployment Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Malawian government has called
upon its people to brace up for a serious unemployment crisis in
the coming years, according to reports reaching here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The country's Ministry of Labor and Manpower Development said
at least 1. 5 million more job seekers will flood the already
saturated job market.
</P>
<P>
Since available jobs cannot sustain such an influx of job
seekers, the ministry foresees "a dramatic increase in
prostitution and violent crime".
</P>
<P>
Already, Malawi is facing an unemployment crisis following the
unsatisfactory performance of the agriculture sector that supports
90 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco, the country's chief money earner, and cotton are
performing poorly on the market, putting thousands more jobs on
the line.
</P>
<P>
Paul Gondwe, an official with the labor ministry, said there
was an imbalance between the rate at which new entrants were
joining the labor market and the rate at which the economy created
new jobs.
</P>
<P>
"This means that over a million new labor force entrants will
have to seek livelihood from subsistence agriculture and any other
ways," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gondwe added that the impact of rapid population growth on the
labor market would continue reducing employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
To match the increasing labor force, the Ministry of Labor and
Manpower Development urges Malawians to invest in family planning
in order to control population growth and to prepare the youth for
self-employment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
