<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Two Lebanese civilians were injured
Thursday morning by stones pelted by Israeli soldiers at the Fatma
Gate along the Lebanese-Israeli border, Lebanese National News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The injured, a father and his five-year-old son, were sent to
hospital immediately after the incident.
</P>
<P>
Local people, angered by cuss broadcast through a tweeter in the
Israeli side in Arabic upon the Lebanese people, anti-Israeli
Hezbollah guerrillas and some Lebanese religious leaders, hurled
stones at the Israeli side along the border. The two were injured
when Israeli soldiers threw stones back.
</P>
<P>
In another related development, one Israeli soldier was
seriously wounded by a stone hurled across the Fatma Gate by
Lebanese demonstrators at the border fence on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh blamed Lebanon for
not deploying its army in the evacuated zone, which was left after
Israel withdrew its troops from south Lebanon on May 24. He also
accused the Lebanese government of organizing anti-Israeli
demonstrations along the border.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli minister said Israel has thus far lodged 82
complaints with the United Nations over these disorders, which
could touch off a dangerous escalation along the borders.
</P>
<P>
Israel has announced that its soldiers can open fire to stop any
invasion into the Israeli territory, including attacks with stones.
So far, no fire has opened at stone-pelters. 
</P>
