<HEADLINE> Turkey Criticized for Setting up New Check Point in Southeast Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Defense Minister Socrates
Hasikos Thursday criticized Turkey for violating the status quo in
southeast Cyprus by establishing a new check point in the area.
</P>
<P>
The check point was set up by the Turkish military with a view
to restrict the movement of U.N. peacekeepers on the island, the
minister told the House Defense Committee.
</P>
<P>
"It looks as if we are going to see a permanent situation,
created in the area of Strovilia, especially after the hoisting of
the Turkish flag and that of the self-styled Turkish Cypriot regime
in occupied Cyprus," Cyprus News Agency quoted the minister as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government is taking the matter seriously and is
taking all the necessary steps to revert the situation to its prior
state, he pledged.
</P>
<P>
The action, taken by the Turkish Cypriot side last Friday, is
certain to have the full backing of Ankara, Hasikos said, stressing
that it is a "clear extension of the occupation."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has lodged protest to the Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash over the move, but so far has received no response.
</P>
<P>
Hasikos said this matter not only affected a small place like
Cyprus, but also humiliated the U.N. too.
</P>
<P>
He said the Cyprus government is in touch with Athens on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
The eastern Mediterranean island of Cyprus has been divided into
the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities since 1974 when Turkish
forces invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed coup in Nicosia seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a republic in
northern Cyprus in 1983 which is only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
