<HEADLINE> Iran's Majlis, Guardians Council Call for Mutual Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran's reformist Majlis (parliament)
and its conservative rival, the Guardians Council (GC), on Thursday
called for mutual cooperation between the two bodies, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between the Majlis and the GC will serve to remove
the problems facing the Iranian people, Majlis speaker Mehdi
Karrubi was quoted as saying in a meeting with several members of
the GC.
</P>
<P>
The 12-member GC supervises elections and examines legislation
passed by the Majlis to ensure it accords with the country's
Islamic principles.
</P>
<P>
In the meeting, Karrubi cautioned against escalation of tension
between political parties which he said will only dishearten the
people.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the GC not to make hasty judgment about
criticism voiced by Majlis members but to approve Majlis
legislation within the framework of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
In response, Mohammad Yazdi, former judicial chief and currently
a leading member in the GC, called for Karrubi's contribution to
help hold negotiations between the Majlis and the GC to solve the
disputes between the two bodies, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Several other GC members at the meeting also called for a
meeting between the GC and the Presiding Board of the Majlis to
reinforce "understanding and coordination" between the two bodies.
</P>
<P>
Iran's sixth parliament, dominated by reformers supporting
President Mohammad Khatami's liberal programs, officially replaced
its conservative predecessor on May 27.
</P>
<P>
It has vowed to overturn conservative laws passed by the fifth
parliament, including amendments to the press law which intended to
put more restrictions on the country's reformist press.
</P>
<P>
Following the overwhelming victory of reformers in February's
parliamentary election, the conservative GC has cancelled election
results in a number of constituencies, in some cases even
transferring the victory of reformers to the conservative hands.
</P>
<P>
A number of seats in the 290-seat new parliament are still
vacant due to the cancellations. Many analysts believe the new
parliament will face a lot of obstacles in passing reformist
legislation, as its power is severely restricted by the
conservative GC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
