leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak will
meet with him next Tuesday in Camp David near Washington to try to
reach a final peace agreement by mid-September.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with Arafat, Abdullah said Jordan
hopes the three-way summit will make substantial progress on the
Palestinian track to pave the way for a just, durable and
comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Arafat thanked Abdullah for supporting the course
of the Palestinians and commended the efforts exerted by the
monarch and his kingdom toward a just and comprehensive peace in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Jordan believes a solution to the Palestinian issue is the core
of the Middle East peace process, without which there will be no
just and genuine peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
During a telephone conversation with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on Wednesday, Abdullah also called on all
parties concerned to do their utmost to guarantee a success of the
summit, and to reach a peace agreement between Israel and the
Palestinians by the September 13 deadline.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom has been a major peace broker between Israel and its
Arab neighbors since it signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994
as the second Arab country after Egypt to reach such a peace deal
with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Jordan stands for a just, durable and comprehensive peace for
all peoples in the region and has been persistent in its support
for the Palestinians to restore their legitimate rights in the
final status talks, including the establishment of an independent
state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The final status talks mainly touched upon the thorniest issues
of borders, the status of Jerusalem, refugees, Jewish settlements
and water sharing arrangements between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has vowed to declare an independent
Palestinian state by September 13 with or without an agreement with
Israel during the final status talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
