<HEADLINE> Direct Flight to be Staged to Protest U.N. Embargo on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A direct flight from Paris to the
Iraqi capital Baghdad will be staged in September to challenge the
decade-old U.N. embargo against Iraq, an official of the Iraqi
Peace, Solidarity and Friendship Organization said here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The flight will most probably be organized by Jean-Marie
Benjamin, a French priest and also a film maker, who declared the
plan in May.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released on May 9, Benjamin said he will organize
another flight from Paris to Baghdad by taking a Boeing passenger
plane with some 300 people on board.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin, along with three other people from Italy, arrived in
Baghdad on April 3, becoming the first group flying to Baghdad
without getting prior permission from the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed an embargo on Iraq since its invasion of Kuwait
in 1990. Every flight to or from Baghdad must be authorized by the
U.N. Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
Iraq claims that as many as 1.3 million people, mostly children
and the elderly, have died as a direct result of the crippling
embargo.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin, who is a resident in Italy, said some pro-Iraq Italian
figures have called for an investigation into the use of depleted
uranium bombs by the U.S. and Britain against Iraq during the 1991
Gulf War, terming it "a crime committed against the Iraqi people."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has claimed radioactivity from the depleted uranium bombs
used by the U.S. and British forces in the Gulf War is the main
cause for the increasing number of cancer patients, which rose from
4,341 in 1991 to 6,158 in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
