<HEADLINE> Ex-French President to Boycott Helsinki Accords Ceremony in Vienna </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Former French President Valery
Giscard d'Estaing will boycott the ceremony commemorating the 25th
anniversary of the Helsinki Accords to be held on July 19 in the
Austrian capital of Vienna.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse quoted the secretary's office of d'Estaing
as saying Thursday that the former president decided to boycott
the ceremony because it will only celebrate the part of the
accords concerning humanitarian cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Helsinki Accords include four parts which respectively
cover security in Europe, cooperation in the economic field,
science, technology and environment, questions relative to
security and cooperation in the Mediterranean, and cooperation in
humanitarian fields and others.
</P>
<P>
D'Estaing has sent a letter to Austrian Foreign Minister Benita
Ferrero Waldner, whose country is the current president of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe which
organizes the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, relations between France and Austria are tense
because of dispute over European Union (EU) sanctions against the
Austrian government which has the far-right Freedom Party members
in it.
</P>
<P>
Austria has called for the lifting of the sanctions imposed in
January, while France, which took over the EU rotating presidency
this month, wants to keep it in force until the European Court of
Human Rights makes a decision. 
</P>
