<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Use Trout to Test Toxicity from Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada is introducing a trout
survival rate as a national standard to test toxic discharge from
mines, the Globe and Mail newspaper said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a new LC-50 test (lethal concentration of 50 percent), some
of the discharge will be dumped into an aquarium and, then, 10
rainbow trout will be added to see if half the fish survive after
96 hours.
</P>
<P>
The idea is that a 50-percent survival rate in the discharged
solution will be non-toxic to trout once the chemical cocktail is
diluted in the streams and rivers where it is dumped.
</P>
<P>
With the newly proposed standard, the federal government will
not impose specific limits on the discharge of mercury and cadmium,
the two highly toxic substances from mines across Canada.
</P>
<P>
But the new regulations propose that the allowable limits of
total suspended solids be reduced to 15 milligrams a liter from 25
milligrams under the Metal Mining Liquid Effluent Regulations
adopted in 1977.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations come after seven years of consultation
among the mining industry, environmentalists, scientists and the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
The proposals do not take effect until they are published in
the Canada Gazette later this year, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
