<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: U.N. Takes Crucial Step Towards Ending Sierra Leone War (by Gu Zhenqiu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Wednesday voted to impose a worldwide ban on the purchase of rough
diamonds from Sierra Leone, where a thriving gem-for-gun business
fans the hard-to-end warfare.
</P>
<P>
The ban imposition sends a strong signal that the U.N.
Security Council, which, under the U.N. Charter, has the primary
responsibility for the maintenance of international peace and
security, intends to get at the root of the conflict in the West
African country.
</P>
<P>
Diamond is at the heart of the tragedy of Sierra Leone. This
precious resource has become the cause of human suffering on a
terrible scale, rather than a source of wealth for national
development.
</P>
<P>
"We have always maintained that the conflict in Sierra Leone
is not about the ideology, tribal or regional difference," Ibrahim
Kamara, the Sierra Leonean permanent representative to the United
Nations, told an open Security Council meeting Wednesday. "It has
nothing to do with the so-called problem of marginalized youths or,
as some political commentators have characterized it, an uprising
by rural poor against the urban elite. The root of the conflict is
and remains diamonds, diamonds and diamonds."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Security Council intends to choke off the
financial sources for the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
to buy weapons or to drag on the conflict in the West African
country.
</P>
<P>
Some 90 percent of Sierra Leone's diamonds, considered to be
of high quality, are under the control of rebels, who smuggle the
rough stones out of the country through Liberia to international
markets. Sales of diamonds falsely labeled as Liberian provide
money to buy guns and other war materials for continuing the fight
in the former British colony.
</P>
<P>
Liberian President Charles Taylor is close to the RUF, the
main rebel group in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Diamond, gold, iron ore and bauxite accounted for about two-
thirds of Sierra Leone's exports before war in the 1990s wrecked
the economy of the West African country.
</P>
<P>
The diamond embargo makes it illegal to buy Sierra Leonean
diamonds, except those that have a certificate of origin from the
government. Since there is no certification process yet in place,
the ban would initially cover all diamonds sales.
</P>
<P>
The London-based organization Global Witness reported in
October that rebels earned 200 million U.S. dollars a year from
1991 to 1999 in illicit diamonds sales.
</P>
<P>
"The illicit export of Sierra Leone diamonds is not only the
root and fuel of the conflict, but also constitutes a major
obstacle to its peaceful resolution," Kamara said.
</P>
<P>
The ban is not against the Sierra Leonean government, which
welcomes the U.N. action.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the U.N. move is a necessary and critical step to
assist the government of Sierra Leone in re-establishing authority
over its diamond-producing regions, and this is one of the
conditions to the lifting of the global embargo, which runs for an
initial period of 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The Council vote and the resolution itself show how the
international community is seriously concerned at the negative
role played by the diamonds in the conflict in Sierra Leone, but
the implementation is another matter. To keep the embargo
effective and equitable requires strong political will and
decisive actions from all governments because their positive
response can help the Sierra Leonean people return to the quiet,
peaceful and productive life they deserve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0074 </DOCNO>
