<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Up 4.1 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- New orders to U.S. factories
rose 4.1 percent in May, the largest increase since the end of
1992, the Commerce Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Factory orders shot up to a seasonally adjusted 385.8 U.S.
billion dollars in May, up from 370.4 billion dollars the month
before. May's rise marked the largest gain since a 4.9 percent
increase posted in December 1992.
</P>
<P>
In April, factory orders fell 3.8 percent, a smaller decline
than the government previously estimated.
</P>
<P>
In another report, the Labor Department said new claims for
unemployment benefits fell by a bigger-than-expected 12,000 last
week to 296,000. Claims had shot up the previous two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Analysts consider claims below 300,000 an indication of a tight
labor market, meaning employers are having trouble finding
qualified workers to fill openings.
</P>
<P>
In the factory orders report, the government said that orders
for electronic and electrical equipment, including household
appliances and communications equipment, surged 26.4 percent in
May. That was the largest increase since August 1997. In April,
electronic orders fell 17.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Transportation equipment orders rose 3.3 percent in May
following a 6.3 percent drop the month before.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile transportation category, factory orders
grew 4.3 percent, the biggest jump since January 1980.
</P>
<P>
Orders for all durable goods, big-ticket manufactured items
expected to last at least three years, rose 6.1 percent in May,
the strongest pace since December. In April, such orders fell 5.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
Orders for non-durable goods, such as food and fuel, grew by 1.
7 percent, following a 1.2 percent drop in April.
</P>
<P>
Shipments, a barometer of current production, rose 1.9 percent
in May, the largest gain since April 1996 and the seventh increase
in the last eight months.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates six times since
June 1999 to slow the economy and keep inflation from escalating.
Some economic reports have suggested the Fed's rate increases are
working to slow growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
