<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Urges African Nations to End "Malaria Taxes" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
Thursday called on African countries to follow the lead of Uganda
and Tanzania to scrap taxes and tariffs on mosquito nets and
insecticides used in the fight against malaria.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is the fastest country to respond to the hard-hitting
pledges made at the historic African Malaria Summit in Nigeria
last April to waive malaria-related taxes and tariffs, said WHO in
a press release here.
</P>
<P>
It has completely scrapped taxes and tariffs on mosquito nets
and insecticides used in the fight against malaria in its June
budget.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania was the first African country to take action on the "
malaria tax" last year by reducing taxes and tariff duty to five
percent, making mosquito nets more affordable at an average price
of 3.5 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to WHO, malaria kills more than one million people a
year worldwide, with nine out of 10 cases in Africa, while it can
be easily prevented by using insecticides and bed nets to stop
mosquitoes that transmit the disease.
</P>
<P>
Prices for nets vary widely across Africa, with prices reported
to be as high as 45 dollars in Swaziland and 30 dollars in Sudan,
putting them completely out of reach of most Africans.
</P>
<P>
WHO estimates that only about three percent of families in
malaria endemic countries use insecticide treated nets, with cost
thought to be a major obstacle for wider use.
</P>
<P>
Most tax and tariff authorities continue to view insecticide
treated nets as textiles instead of pharmaceutical materials with
the potential to save lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece, Portugal Record Highest Rate of Road Deaths in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Portugal and Greece recorded the
highest road death rate in the 15-nation European Union (EU), the
EU statistical office, Eurostat, reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the data, the road death rate varies considerably
among the EU member states. In 1998, the average road death rate
was 114 per million inhabitants. The highest rates in the EU were
Portugal with 243 and Greece with 212. France and Spain recorded
152 and 151 respectively, also well above the EU average.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the safest roads were in Sweden and Britain, with 60
and 61 deaths per million inhabitants, respectively.
</P>
<P>
During the 1990s, the road death rate fell in almost every EU
member state, but the only exception was Greece, where the rate
was up by five percent between 1990 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
In the previous decade, the biggest reductions occurred in
Austria (-41%), and Finland (-40%), while Britain and Spain (both -
35%), Sweden (-33%), Germany (-32%), and Denmark (-31%) all
performed better than the EU average (-26%) in cutting deaths.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat said road accidents caused the death of 42,600 people
in the EU in 1998. In spite of increasing traffic, the number of
road deaths in the EU fell from 56,400 in 1990 to 43,500 in 1996,
a reduction of almost 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, with the number of deaths remaining virtually
unchanged from 1996 to 1998, progress in road safety seems to have
been more limited in recent years because big differences still
remain, though the death rate has fallen in most EU countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
