<HEADLINE> Venus Williams Wins Family Affair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Venus Williams of the United States
won the battle of the Williams sisters, defeating Serena 6-2, 7-6
(7-3) in an enthralling women's semi-final contest at the
Wimbledon tennis championships on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The elder of the two always seemed to be in control despite the
numerous breaks of serve which the players gave away on a frequent
basis.
</P>
<P>
After a comprehensive first set Serena found her feet in the
second but with every powerful stroke she struck the return was
often far better and the tie-break proved to be a step too far as
Venus booked a place in her first Wimbledon final.
</P>
<P>
After the game a slightly jaded Venus admitted that the match
was always in the balance.
</P>
<P>
"If it was the final it would have been different," said the
winning Williams sister.
</P>
<P>
"It could have gone either way but I was able to stay tough. I
played so well because Serena played well. We were relaxed before
the contest but once it had started it was chins down," she said.
</P>
<P>
The opening set looked to be going to serve until the fourth
game when Venus made her younger sister pay for a number of
uncharacteristic double faults.
</P>
<P>
But Serena recovered in the following game as she matched Venus
with some terrific cross-court shots to break back.
</P>
<P>
However the elder of the pair used all her experience to take
the next game on Serena's serve, and it then seemed a formality
for Venus as she cruised to a 6-2 opening set advantage.
</P>
<P>
Fifth seed Venus had reached the Wimbledon quarter-finals for
the last two years and it always appeared that she may go one
better at the expense of her sister.
</P>
<P>
Serena had time to collect her thoughts in the one-minute break
between sets and came out of the stalls prepared to remedy the
situation in which she had found herself in.
</P>
<P>
Her youthful exuberance shone through as she played her Venus
around the entire surface of Center Court to win a valuable break
in the first game of the second set.
</P>
<P>
The watching crowd were now being treated to power and
precision as the athleticism of the sisters came to a fore,
spreading returns from side to side of the court like a swinging
pendulum.
</P>
<P>
The match was going to be decided on temperament - the sister
who could steady her nerves on their way to winning the crucial
points.
</P>
<P>
The eighth game saw Serena wilt as Venus raced away to a 40-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
The eighth seed's shoulders began to droop as she struck an
over-hit shot to hand her break advantage back to Venus.
</P>
<P>
The elder sister nearly gave away a break in the 11th game,
when she was hauled back to deuce after being 40-0 up, but Serena
failed to capitalise when she struck a forehand shot fractionally
wide.
</P>
<P>
The tie-break saw five points out of the first seven go against
the server as both sets of players had to contend with some
immaculate returning.
</P>
<P>
But it was Venus again who proved that experience is
irreplaceable as her sister began to make mistakes on her service
giving away a double fault on the deciding point. 
</P>
</TEXT>
