<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Wins Right to Host 2006 World Cup Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Germany has won in a four-nation
race to host the 2006 World Cup finals, FIFA President Sepp
Blatter announced today at the international football federation's
headquarters in Zurich.
</P>
<P>
Germany won by 12-11 in the final round of voting with one
abstention, Blatter said. Morocco went out in the first round
after collecting only three votes and England in the second round
having picked up two votes at that stage from the 24-member
executive committee of the FIFA.
</P>
<P>
A fifth candidate, Brazil, withdrew from the competition, only
two days before the FIFA's final decision.
</P>
<P>
Blatter said that the FIFA had faced a choice between
innovation and trusting a new continent or sticking with the
established football countries. He congratulated head of the
German bid committee Franz Beckenbauer for Germany's victory.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, South Africa had been tipped to win the vote,
with unofficial reports saying its margin of victory might be as
high as 14-10 following Brazil's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The German chancellor, Gerhard Schroder, as well as a host of
German sporting personalities were also in Zurich to lend weight
to the country's bid.
</P>
<P>
After the vote, Beckenbauer thanked FIFA for its confidence in
Germany, and said he was "a little surprised but very happy" with
the result.
</P>
<P>
The votes were as follows:
</P>
<P>
In the first round: England 5, Germany 10, Morocco 3, South
Africa 6. Morocco was eliminated.
</P>
<P>
In the second round: England 2, Germany 11, South Africa 11.
England was eliminated.
</P>
<P>
In the third and final round: Germany 12, South Africa 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
