<HEADLINE> PSA Records Double-Digit Throughput Growth over First Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Port of Singapore Authority
Corporation Limited (PSA) recorded double-digit throughput growth
both in Singapore and overseas in the first half of 2000 and has
been accorded the highest credit ratings by two international
credit rating companies, its chairman Yeo Ning Hong pleasantly
told a press conference here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yeo affirmed that PSA has achieved a strong year-on-year
throughput growth of 12.8 from January to June 2000, handling a
total of 8.6 million twenty-foot Equivalent Units (TEUs) at its
container terminals in Singapore, and its overseas terminals
handled a total of 1.26 million TEUs which represented a growth of
more than 70 percent over the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that PSA has been accorded a corporate credit
rating of "AAA" by Standard &AMP; Poor's (S&AMP;P) and an indicative
rating of "Aa1" for its prospective unsecured long-term foreign
debt securities by Moody's Investors Service (Moody's).
</P>
<P>
He described the throughput growths and credit ratings as four
happiness to his company and ask all present to share with him the
happiness.
</P>
<P>
Commenting the performance of PSA's two joint ventures in
Dalian and Fuzhou, China, he said "China has been doing very well
in first half of this year in terms of container throughput,"
adding it registered "a high double-digit growth."
</P>
<P>
"To my mind, China is doing very well in its economy and imports
and exports really reflect overall economy of China," he said
further.
</P>
<P>
On the ratings, Yeo said that "AAA" is the highest credit
rating assigned by S&AMP;P and he was "extremely happy" and "extremely
honored".
</P>
<P>
"The credit ratings assigned by S&AMP;P and Moody's reelect their
assessment of PSA's re-eminent strengths in its industry and very
strong financial position," he said with full smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
Yeo stressed that the rating is given to PSA as a company, on
the basis of PSA's financial standing and PSA's performance, not
because of its link or relations with the government.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, a total of 15.9 million TEUs, around 80 percent of
which were transshipment containers, passed through PSA's ports in
Singapore and PSA's financial position was very strong with
revenues around 1.5 billion U.S. dollars, profit after taxes
approximately 450 million U.S. dollars and assets of around 4.7
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
