<HEADLINE> Vietnam Maps out Overall Plan of Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has mapped out an overall
plan of foreign trade with annual export and import growth rate of
between 14 and 15 percent in the next five years, Vietnam's
official news agency VNA reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the target, the Ministry of Trade (MoT) will take
drastic measures to promote exports and imports.
</P>
<P>
While strengthening relationships with existing large markets
in the Asia-Pacific region, according to the plan, the MoT will
also broaden business relationships with Russia, East European
countries, the United States, the Middle East, Africa and Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
In another move to help boost exports and prevent the trade
deficit from growing, the MoT is proposing solutions to combine
exports with imports through barter trade with the Philippines,
Myanmar, Laos and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government plans to improve the legal framework
for import-export activities while local authorities will focus on
realizing trade policies and managing their implementation by
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam posted an export turnover of about 6.43 billion U.S.
dollars in the first six months of this year, a year-on-year
increase of 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country hopes to increase its export turnover to 13.2
billion U.S. dollars by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of this year, Vietnam imported more
than 7.1 billion U.S. dollars worth of raw materials for
production, nearly 33 percent more than the same period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
