<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Unveils New Policies to Boost Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has unveiled
a series of policies aimed at improving food security in the
country, Rwanda News Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The new policies focus on increased production of such crops as
rice, maize, wheat and sorghum, which can be stored for a long
time, said Agriculture, Live Stock and Forestry Minister Ephraim
Kabayija before the parliament.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted as saying that special programs for crops like
cassava, beans and Irish potatoes which do well in some parts of
the country are to be embarked on.
</P>
<P>
As far as live stock is concerned, Kabayija said, the
government will introduce cross-breed animals through artificial
insemination and importation of high breed animals especially
cows, which give high yield of milk and meat.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that so far 1,800 calves have been born by
artificial insemination and over 1,600 high breed cows were
imported from Uganda, South Africa and Germany, with another 400
cows to be imported soon.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, a number of fish ponds have been
constructed and 200,000 fish have been planted in different ponds
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that in the field of agricultural modernization,
his ministry intends to emphasize on the intensification,
specialization and commercialization of agriculture geared towards
making a tangible contribution to the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Over 91 percent of the Rwandan population depend on agriculture
and the country has been in the reformulation of the agricultural
policy with intent to increase agricultural production of food and
cash crops since 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
