<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Problems Persist in Eritrea: WFP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Despite a recent peace agreement
between Eritrea and Ethiopia, hundreds of thousands of
war-affected Eritreans will continue to need large amounts of food
aid for some time to come, the World Food Program (WFP) said here
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The food organization announced that it will be providing food
relief until next April to 750,000 internally displaced and
war-affected people in Eritrea, while the non-governmental
organizations and other agencies will supply food for another
320,000 displaced in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to Kofi Owusu-Tieku, WFP's Emergency Coordinator in
Eritrea, a great number of people are still uprooted and as there
will be no harvest for them, they will be dependent on
international food aid this year and well into next year.
</P>
<P>
Kofi noted that the bulk of displaced civilians are farmers
from the Gash Barka region, Eritrea's breadbasket, which produces
between 60 to 80 percent of grain consumed in Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Most of the people in need of food assistance are women and
children who carry on living in make-shift camps, dry riverbeds
and caves, Kofi said.
</P>
<P>
The full cost of providing 126,000 tons of food to the 750,000
displaced and deportees is estimated at 79 million U.S. dollars,
WFP said, promising to continue its food supply to 94,000 Eritrean
refugees who fled westward into neighboring Sudan during the
conflict between the two countries in May this year.
</P>
<P>
These people will still need food aid when they return home,
the U.N. agency said.
</P>
<P>
Since May this year, WFP has provided 5,415 tons of mixed food
commodities such as cereals, pulses, vegetable oil and corn soya
blend to Eritrea and 1,250 tons to the refugees in Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD Calls on France to Continue Privatization, Opening Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) Thursday called on France to
continue privatizing enterprises and opening up market to
competition.
</P>
<P>
In a report on French economy, OECD also confirmed an earlier
prediction that the nation's gross domestic product will grow by 3
percent this year and 2.9 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
However, it pointed out that French economy is not successful
in creating more enterprises though growth does provide more jobs.
</P>
<P>
The number of new enterprises created each year has been
falling since 1994, despite a slight improvement in 1999, and the
number of newly created enterprises this year was even smaller
than that in the mid-1990s, said the report.
</P>
<P>
OECD blamed the French government intervention for the poor
performance of enterprises and expressed its hope that France will
also open up its electricity, natural gas, railway and post
service after having done so with its telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The organization also warned that France's economy might be
restrained in the future by "over-heating symptom" such as tension
in labor market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
