<HEADLINE> Stojkovic to Replace Boskov as Yugoslavia Coach - Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia's veteran midfielder
Dragan Stojkovic will replace Vujadin Boskov as national team
manager, the daily Sportski Zurnal said on Thursday citing sources
in the Yugoslav Football Federation (FSJ).
</P>
<P>
Veteran playmaker Dejan Savicevic, who missed the Euro 2000
finals owing to injury, will join Stojkovic as the technical
director, the daily said, adding that the appointments would be
decided at a session of the FSJ executive board on July 22.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said it expected Stojkovic, 35, to take over from
Boskov at the end of the year after three 2002 World Cup
qualifying matches against Luxembourg, Russia and the Faroe
Islands.
</P>
<P>
Several Yugoslav media called for Boskov's resignation after
the team was crushed 6-1 by the Netherlands in the Euro 2000
quarter-finals, having scraped through to the last eight.
</P>
<P>
Many said Stojkovic, who is based in Japan and nearing the end
of his playing career, would be an ideal replacement for the 69-
year old manager. 
</P>
