<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South African President Laments Soccer Bid Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 6 (Xinhua) -- President Thabo Mbeki on
Thursday expressed deep disappointment at South Africa's failure
to win the bid for the 2006 soccer World Cup, saying it was "a
tragic day for Africa".
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Pretoria, he said this development was a setback to
efforts to gain for Africa the recognition it deserved on the
sporting world. His address was broadcast live on national
television.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said he believed South Africa's bid was sound but the
executive of soccer's world body, FIFA, obviously had a different
view.
</P>
<P>
FIFA's executive voted 12-11 in favor of Germany hosting the
tournament. One member of the executive, New Zealand's
representative, abstained from the vote.
</P>
<P>
The bidding process had been a hard fought and even bruising at
times, Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
He congratulated Germany for its victory, saying South Africa
would support the bid winner.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said South Africa's bid committee and the South African
Football Association had made South Africa a "very proud nation
indeed".
</P>
<P>
"Your efforts cannot be faulted and I'm sure the experience in
bidding was an empowering one," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki thanked South Africa's bidding team chief executive Danny
Jordaan and its president, Irvin Khoza, for their hard work and
sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Mbeki was flanked by former president Nelson Mandela
and Deputy President Jacob Zuma as they awaited the announcement
in a big circular room in the Union Buildings in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki ended his speech by saying that there would be other
opportunities for the country to host major sporting events and
South Africa should learn from this in order to equip itself for
other events.
</P>
<P>
"The next time we will win," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
