<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africans Slam European Domination in Soccer Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 6 (Xinhua) -- South Africans slammed
European domination of world soccer following Germany's narrow
victory over South Africa in voting on bids for the 2006 soccer
World Cup on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Durban mayor Obed Mlaba labelled the decision "international
racism" while South African bid committee member Selwyn Nathan
described the announcement in Zurich as a further proof of "the
gulf between Africa and Europe".
</P>
<P>
"A large majority of FIFA (soccer's governing body) still see
Africa as backward. To them soccer is a European sport and not a
global one," said Nathan.
</P>
<P>
Mlaba also lashed out at New Zealand's decision to abstain from
the final vote saying that it was a cunning ploy to defeat FIFA
president Sepp Blatter and his ideal to take soccer to all corners
of the globe.
</P>
<P>
Twelve members of FIFA's executive voted for Germany and 11 for
South Africa, with Charles Dempsey of New Zealand withdrawing at
the crucial moment.
</P>
<P>
Former South African soccer coach Clive Barker slammed the
inconsistency of the voting, saying it was scandalous that New
Zealand abstained at the death.
</P>
<P>
Barker cited the first two rounds of voting as being completely
inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
"How can England get five votes in the first round and only two
in the second? Surely the delegates who voted for England in the
first round should have voted for them in the second.
</P>
<P>
"How can they just change tack in a matter of minutes?" Barker
asked.
</P>
<P>
South African Bid Committee president Irvin Khoza also lashed
out at Dempsey.
</P>
<P>
"Dempsey has betrayed the South African people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I do not see how a man can vote in the first two rounds and
then not vote in the third and final round. FIFA should
investigate this," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bid committee chief executive Danny Jordaan hit out at FIFA's
failure to address the European domination and expressed his
disappointment at having been blocked at the final hurdle.
</P>
<P>
"Africa is one of the biggest blocs in FIFA," Jordaan told a
news conference after the announcement.
</P>
<P>
"There is often a reference to the FIFA membership as the '
footballing family'. You can't have a family and feed only one
child and leave the others to starve," Jordaan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
