<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's First Coastal Defense Museum to Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Museum of Coastal
Defense, the first of its kind in Hong Kong, is near completion
and scheduled to open to the public on July 25, Director of
Leisure and Cultural Services Paul Leung Sai-wah said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The museum, located on the headland to the south of the Lei Yue
Mun Pass in Shau Kei Wan, is developed on the former Lei Yue Mun
Fort, covering an area of 34,200 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the Permanent exhibition at the museum is "Six
Hundred Years of Coastal Defense in Hong Kong." In the 11 casemate
galleries, different periods of development in the coastal defense
of Hong Kong and its neighboring area are illustrated.
</P>
<P>
From the museum's exhibition galleries, visitors could trace
the history of Hong Kong's coastal defense over the past six
hundred years.
</P>
<P>
The Lei Yue Mun Fort was built in 1887 by the British to defend
the eastern approach to the Victoria Harbor.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the museum began in October 1997 and was
completed in 1999, with a budget of around 300 million HK dollars
(38.46 million U.S. dollars). The museum was then handed over to
the Museum management for exhibition fabrication. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK Int'l Airport to Scale New Heights  by Ou Sa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong International Airport (
HKIA), which celebrated its second anniversary Thursday, is
consolidating its position as a major passenger and cargo hub.
</P>
<P>
"Already 28 percent of passengers at HKIA use the airport to
transfer to other destinations. As the government of Hong Kong
negotiates more air services agreements to expand our network of
air routes, we are putting in place measures to better serve the
needs of this rapidly growing segment of our business," said Dr.
Victor Fung Kwok-king, chairman of the Airport Authority (AA), on
the occasion.
</P>
<P>
HKIA has much to celebrate on the anniversary, with a
succession of new records for passenger and cargo growth set in
the past few months, including more than 31.6 million passengers
and 2.11 million tonnes of airfreight that passed through HKIA in
the 12 months until May this year. The calendar year records to
date are 30.8 million passengers in 1996, and 1.9 million tonnes
of cargo in 1999.
</P>
<P>
AA was undertaking the necessary planning in anticipation of
continued robust growth, particularly of cargo, according to Dr
Fung.
</P>
<P>
In the short term, four more cargo aircraft stands would be
added, bringing the total number of dedicated cargo aircraft
stands to 17.
</P>
<P>
Tenders were also invited recently to work on the new airport
master plan, the Strategic Overview of Major Airport Development
Study, which would serve as the blueprint for growth as the
airport progresses towards its ultimate design capacity of 87
million passengers and 9 million tonnes of cargo.
</P>
<P>
AA has planned to provide new and improved services and
facilities to achieve quicker turnarounds for airlines and
passengers. These include moving bags of transfer passengers
between aircraft at a faster rate and positioning connecting
aircraft at gates that were closer to each other.
</P>
<P>
Other developments bode well for the airport. The tourism
sector was showing good signs of recovery with 10.7 million
visitors in Hong Kong last year.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Tourist Association expected that number to
increase by 6.8 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The opening of Hong Kong Disneyland theme park in 2005 and
China's anticipated entry to the World Trade Organization would
have profound impacts on air traffic and airport operations for
many years to come, said Fung.
</P>
<P>
HKIA's role as a gateway to the Chinese mainland will develop
strongly following the conclusion of the air services agreement
between the mainland and Hong Kong in February this year.
</P>
<P>
"We now enjoy direct air links to 40 cities across the mainland,
" Dr Fung said. "This impressive network, combined with our
extensive international flights, place us in an enviable position
to capture the potential of this vast and immensely promising
market."
</P>
<P>
Fung said the development of logistics centers and a marine
cargo handling facility would allow the airport to evolve into a
major transshipment center for the Pearl Rive Delta and southern
mainland cities.
</P>
<P>
Studies were also underway to transform HKIA's vast commercial
land bank into "a great Airport City of East Asia," including
facilities such as an exhibition and convention center, hotels,
commercial offices, and recreational complexes.
</P>
<P>
HKIA, located on a 1,248-hectare site at Chek Lap Kok on the
northern side of Lantau Island, began regular services on July 6,
1998, after Chinese President Jiang Zemin officially opened it on
July 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
