<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Repeats Warning Against Forest Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- As Turkey is under a spell of intense
heat, the Forest Ministry on Thursday again rang an alarm against
forest fires across the country, reported Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The ministry in a written statement asked people not to light
fires and throw cigarette buds close to forests, adding that fire
alarm call No.177 should be made when smoke is seen from forests.
</P>
<P>
The Governor offices in various provinces should maintain bans
on access to forests, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Forest Ministry instructed all its units to be well prepared
against any fire hazard.
</P>
<P>
Although the ministry has more than once issued warnings this
summer, forest fires are appearing to be on the rise.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday alone, 24 forest fires occured throughout the
country. Around 78 hectares of forest were destroyed in the fires.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government attaches great importance to prevention
of forest fire in the country, which has a total of 26 percent of
lands covered by forests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
