<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Asian Nations to Enhance Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Indian External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh, who inaugurated
the one-day meeting, urged countries in the region to exploit the
vast potential for joint cooperation in infrastructure,
agriculture, information technology, food processing, human
resources and other area.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the fallout of the East Asian Crisis, he said that
regional cooperation assumes a special role and significance in
the current global economic scenario.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by Ministers of State for Foreign
Affairs from Bangladesh, India, Sri Lanka, Myanmar and Thailand.
Nepal attended the meeting as an observer.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement issued at the conclusion of the meeting said
that the ministers noted that the global economy is now on a path
of recovery after the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it is the right time to provide momentum to the
BIMST-EC by enhancing economic, commercial and technical
cooperation among the member countries, both at the government and
private sector levels, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The meeting welcomed the recommendations of the BIMST-EC
Economic Forum, held here on Monday, relating to trade
facilitation both in the context of establishment of a Free Trade
Area in the future and/or a Preferential Trading Arrangement in
the immediate stage.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also commended the proposal for setting up a joint
BIMST-EC Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The BIMST-EC, an economic grouping comprising three South Asian
nations and two Southeast Asian nations, was formed in 1997 in
Bangkok, Thailand. The second ministerial meeting was held in
Dhaka, Bangladesh, in December 1998. The fourth ministerial
meeting will be held in Yangon, Myanmar, in February 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
