<HEADLINE> Floodwaters Kill 12 in Northern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Floodwaters caused by Tropical Storm
Edeng and Typhoon Ditang have killed 12 people since Tuesday and
injured five others while one people remains missing in the
northern Philippines, the government said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The National Disaster Coordination Council (NDCC) said Thursday
night in a report that 121,725 families have been affected by the
bad weather and 4,675 families still stay in different evacuation
centers set up by the government.
</P>
<P>
The storm inundated hundreds of villages in the region and
damaged near 500 houses, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Some roads remain impassable to all types of vehicles as of
Thursday afternoon due to rampaging floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC estimated that at least 70 million pesos (1.75 million
U.S. dollars) worth of crops were destroyed by the floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
Scores of trucks and rubber boats have been dispatched by
different government agencies to extend emergency assistance to
affected people, said the NDCC.
</P>
<P>
The weather authorities said although the storm and typhoon are
moving out of the country, southwest monsoon will continue to
bring rains over the western sections of Luzon and Visayas in the
next 24 hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
