<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Export Wheat to Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan will export wheat to
Afghanistan and an agreement to this effect will be made shortly,
an official at the Ministry of Food and Agriculture here said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The issue was discussed during a recent high level Taliban
delegation's visit to Pakistan, the sources said, adding that
another Taliban delegation will visit here shortly to finalize the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the Taliban regime has expressed its
desire to import a maximum of one million tons of wheat from
Pakistan on a rational price.
</P>
<P>
Owing to unprecedented drought in 30 years, Afghanistan is
expected to suffer from shortage of wheat soon.
</P>
<P>
There is no ban on "government to government" supply of wheat
to Afghanistan despite the U.N. Security Council sanctions on
Afghanistan, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
He further said that Pakistan is enjoying a bumper wheat crop
this year and is in a position to earn 500 million U.S. dollars
through the export of this commodity.
</P>
<P>
According to official estimates, there will be a surplus of
around two million tons of wheat in Pakistan and the export of one
million tons will not create any shortage in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
