<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't to Install 20,000 Computers for Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has set
aside some 600 million pesos (15 million U.S. dollars) for the
installation of 20,000 desktop computers in public high schools
nationwide to help students become computer literate.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Manuel Roxas of the Department of Trade and Industry
said Thursday in a report that knowledge of computers will help
bring the economic opportunities of technology to the youth,
particularly those living in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
He said the estimated 600 million peso will be spent over the
next 12 months as the government's counterpart fund for the
donation of brand-new and used computers to public high schools by
private corporations.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly 600 million pesos will be dedicated to wiring up a
quarter of our national high schools throughout the country,"
Roxas said.
</P>
<P>
The government's initiative on education was parallel to the
private sector-led "Personal Computer-for-Public High Schools"
program, he added.
</P>
<P>
Roxas said the private sector has responded enthusiastically to
the program by giving their donations of cash and equipment.
</P>
<P>
"What will happen is there will be computer laboratories and
workshop rooms that will be instituted," Roxas said.
</P>
<P>
There will be 20 desktop computers for each laboratory, and one
laboratory for every national high school for 1,000 high schools,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
