<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Predicts 3.8% GDP Growth for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Belgium on Thursday revised
prediction of this year's economic growth, expecting its gross
domestic product (GDP) to increase by 3.8 percent instead of 3.2
percent as previously forecast.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Belgian Planning Bureau predicted a 3.1 percent
growth for the coming year, up from a former figure of 2.6 percent.
This is compared with a 2.7 percent and a 2.5 percent growth
respectively for 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
The office based the results mainly on increase in the
country's exports and domestic demand, and on an increasingly
improved employment rate, which, at 58.2 percent in 1999, is
expected to reach 59.0 percent this year and rise further to 59.6
percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The planning bureau added that Belgium's inflation rate would
fall to 2.1 percent this year and further to 1.4 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
It expected investment in small and medium-sized enterprises to
increase to a level as high as at the beginning of the 1990s.
</P>
</TEXT>
