<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meteorological Satellite Sends First Visible Light Cloud Picture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Fengyun 2 meteorological
satellite, which was recently launched by China, has sent back its
first visible light nephogram (picture of clouds) to the State
Satellite Meteorological Center.
</P>
<P>
This was announced here today by Wen Kegang, director of the
China Meteorological Administration.
</P>
<P>
The nephogram clearly shows the eastern coast of Africa, the
entire Indian Ocean, the western part of the Pacific Ocean, the
whole of Asia, and the continent of Australia. China lies in the
upper-central part of the nephogram.
</P>
<P>
The good quality of the nephogram indicates that the
multichannel scanning radiator, the satellite's functions and the
digital receiver are all working well, Wen said.
</P>
<P>
Having analyzed the nephogram, a group of experts observed that
there is a frontal cloud system affecting Lake Baikal in Russia,
the western part of Mongolia and the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau in
China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another cyclonic cloud system is covering the
country's northeastern and northern areas, the Yellow River and
Huai River area, the Yangtze River and Huai River area, and the
eastern part of southwestern China, the meteorologists said.
</P>
<P>
Also clearly seen are clouds of the No.3 typhoon in the Pacific
Ocean and clouds belonging to the No.4 tropical storm which has
hit the eastern part of the South China Sea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
