<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gathering Marks Discovery of Dunhuang Library Cave (With Details) ( 1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A grand gathering to mark the
centennial of the discovery of the Dunhuang Library Cave and the
birth of Dunhuang studies was held here today at the Great Hall of
the People.
</P>
<P>
The gathering, sponsored by the Ministry of Culture, the Gansu
provincial government and the State Cultural Heritage
Administration, is a major event in the country's two-month
commemoration of the world-stunning find.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the meeting, Vice-Premier Li Lanqing expressed
his gratitude to researchers, archaeologists, heritage protectors
and other experts for their great contributions to Dunhuang relics
preservation and Dunhuang studies.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people should carry forward all the outstanding
cultural traditions of the nation while eagerly learning from
foreign countries to build a modern socialist culture with Chinese
characteristics, Li said.
</P>
<P>
As an important cradle of Chinese civilization, the western
region, where Dunhuang is located, has abundant cultural relics.
The westward development project decided by the central
authorities provides the western region with a historic
opportunity, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li also urged the western localities to staunchly safeguard
their cultural heritage while speeding up the development of
tourism resources.
</P>
<P>
Li Tieying, president of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences
(CASS), told the meeting that he hopes that scholars and experts
nationwide would continue to compile, study and publish the
precious Dunhuang documents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gathering Marks Discovery of Dunhuang Library Cave (With Details) ( 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Minister of Culture Sun Jiazheng, who also attended the meeting,
said that Dunhuang art reflects both European and Asian cultural
features, and exemplifies the outstanding achievements made by the
ancient people of China.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 experts and officials participated in the
commemorative meeting.
</P>
<P>
In 1900, Taoist priest Wang Yuanlu discovered a cave at the
Mogao Grottoes in Dunhuang, containing more than 50,000 sutras,
documents and paintings from nearly 10 dynasties, ranging from the
4th to the 11th century.
</P>
<P>
The Mogao Grottoes of Dunhuang, popularly known as the Thousand
Buddha Caves, were carved out of sandstone cliffs stretching about
1,600 meters along the eastern side of Mingsha Hill, 25 km
southeast of Dunhuang.
</P>
<P>
A Tang Dynasty inscription records that the first cave in the
Mogao Grottoes was carved in 366 A.D. Despite erosion and man-made
destruction, most of the 492 caves are well preserved, with
frescoes covering an area of 45,000 sq m, more than 2,000 colored
sculptured figures and five wooden eaves overhanging the caves.
</P>
<P>
According to archaeologists, the caves are the greatest and
most consummate repository of Buddhist art in the world. The
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (
UNESCO) put the Mogao Grottoes on the World Heritage List in 1987.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a large-scale exhibition of Dunhuang art is now
being held at the Museum of Chinese History here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
