<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 50-50 Chance for Three-Way to Succeed: Barak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
said Thursday the chances were 50-50 for his summit with U.S.
President Bill Clinton and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to
succeed.
</P>
<P>
The summit will be an important opportunity for Israel and
Palestinians to resolve the key issues concerning the peace
process, but it is hard to say for now whether the summit could
achieve satisfactory results, Barak said in an interview with
Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Barak said the Israeli delegation will do everything possible to
reach a peace agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that he will not sign an agreement that may
threaten Israel's national security.
</P>
<P>
He will not agree to return to the 1967 border line and that
almost 90 percent of the Jewish settlements in the occupied
territories will remain under Israeli sovereignty, he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton announced Wednesday to hold a summit
with Barak and Arafat starting next Tuesday at Camp David near
Washington. The summit will try to reach a framework agreement on
final-status issues such as Jerusalem, borders, refugees, Jewish
settlements and water.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the summit received mixed reactions among
Barak's coalition partners and other political parties in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Natan Sharansky of Yisrael Ba'aliya, Barak's
coalition partner with four seats in the Knesset (parliament),
announced on Wednesday that his party has decided to resign from
the coalition and he will submit the resignation letter to Barak
during next Sunday's cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Sharansky blamed Barak of keeping the coalition party leaders in
the dark about the ongoing Israeli-Palestinian final-status talks.
He also accused Barak of making too many concessions to the
Palestinians regarding territorial transfer.
</P>
<P>
Barak's One Israel bloc's largest coalition partner Shas party
called on Barak to finalize the "red lines" that should not be
crossed in the negotiations. Shas said its leader Eli Yishai will
not be joining the delegation to the summit.
</P>
<P>
The National Religious Party said it will leave the coalition if
Barak goes to the summit.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Likud party has prepared a no-confidence motion
against the Barak-led coalition in the Knesset to expressed its
objection to the summit.
</P>
<P>
But Meretz party leader Yossi Sarid said the summit would be "
the last chance for peace with the Palestinians...and that chance
must be used."
</P>
<P>
Sarid added that the party would back Barak if he works for
peace and the party "trusts Barak to arrive at the best agreement
possible and will support any agreement signed."
</P>
<P>
Barak said he will call a cabinet meeting before going to the
summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
