<HEADLINE> Roundup: Syrian Hijacker Shot Dead Aboard Jordanian Plane by Wang Bingfei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Security officers on board a Royal
Jordanian (RJ) Airbus-320 liner shot dead a Syrian national
Wednesday night as he was hijacking the plane.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen passengers on board were slightly injured by shrapnels
as a hand grenade set off by the hijacker exploded.
</P>
<P>
Police told Xinhua on Thursday that the hijacking happened 10
minutes after the national flag carrier airliner took off from the
Queen Alia International Airport in southern Amman Wednesday night,
when the Syrian rose from his seat with a pistol and a grenade in
his hands.
</P>
<P>
He demanded that the plane be diverted from its course to Syrian
capital Damascus to any airport in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The man, identified as Mohamood Reezq, a Syrian national in his
late 30s, was seeking political asylum in Germany after he failed
to obtain a visa from German embassies in the region to join his
German wife there.
</P>
<P>
A brother of the hijacker and a son and a daughter from his
German wife were also on board the plane, but they did not take
part in the highjacking effort, police said.
</P>
<P>
Security officers on board the airliner shot dead the man when
he was trying to break into the cockpit, but the plain-clothed
officers were unable to prevent the Syrian from setting off his
grenade.
</P>
<P>
The confrontation lasted about two minutes, a police officer who
asked not to be named told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The crew on board managed to pilot the plane back and safely
landed it at the Queen Alia airport.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen of the some 80 passengers aboard were slightly injured
in the explosion but none of the security officers were hurt,
police said.
</P>
<P>
The injured were rushed to the King Hussein Medical Center, a
military hospital compound in western Amman, for emergency cares
soon after the plane touched down.
</P>
<P>
Doctor Manmood al-Yamani, a senior surgeon and member of the
rescue team at the military hospital, said none of the victims was
seriously injured and 14 of them have been released from the
hospital by Thursday noon.
</P>
<P>
Security measures have been tightened at the Queen Alia airport,
one of the three international airports in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Intelligence officers are investigating how the Syrian hijacker
sneaked into the plane with a gun and a pistol without being
detected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
