<HEADLINE> Jerusalem District Attorney Suggests Netanyahu Not Be Indicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Jerusalem district attorney
has recommended that former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu not
be indicted for alleged bribe-taking, Israel Radio reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The attorney, Moshe Lador, said the testimony of state witness
Avner Amedi is problematic and there is no sufficient evidence to
convict the ex-premier.
</P>
<P>
State Attorney Edna Arbel has reportedly not yet taken a
decision on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police recommended in late March that Netanyahu be
arraigned on corruption charges in a bribery and theft case,
following a seven-month investigation on allegations that Netanyahu
and his wife had illegally accepted free services from a private
contractor, Avner Amedi, and kept official gifts after he left the
office last July.
</P>
<P>
It is up to the state attorney to decide whether to put
Netanyahu on trial.
</P>
<P>
The police launched the probe last October after contractor
Amedi, realizing that Netanyahu was no longer able to fulfill
promises after leaving office, sent a bill worth 110,000 U.S.
dollars to the Prime Minister's Office for his services. 
</P>
<P>
During the investigation, in which 100 people were questioned,
the police also found that Netanyahu continued keeping scores of
valuable gifts including paintings and silver and gold objects he
received while in office. 
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli laws, the gifts should have been handed
over to the state after Netanyahu left office July 1999, two months
after he was trounced by Ehud Barak in the national elections.
</P>
<P>
This was the second time in three years that the police
suggested criminal charges against Netanyahu. In 1997, the police
recommended that he be charged with fraud and breach of trust for
appointing a crony as attorney general in an alleged attempt to
influence a corruption investigation against one of his political
allies.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors dropped that case after failing to find sufficient
evidence to support the charges.
</P>
<P>
If finally granted an acquittal, Netanyahu may still have
chances to make a comeback to the political arena. He is enjoying a
rising popularity as a Gallup Poll recently found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
