<HEADLINE> Writethru: Malaysia's Weapon Heist Drama Ends with Surrender of 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The arms heist and hostage-
taking drama in Malaysia since Sunday ended Thursday evening when
all 27 members of the group involved gave themselves up.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two of them have been arrested and five admitted to
hospital with gunshot wounds, two of them seriously injured,
Defense Minister Najib Tun Razak said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The security forces took steps to get the group to surrender,
including throwing a tight cordon around their hideout at Bukit
Jenalek in Sauk in the northern state Perak, the minister told a
press conference at the Kati police station near Sauk, according
to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deputy Prime Minister and Home Minister Abdullah
Ahmad Badawi told a media conference here that the government is
thankful that the Sauk hostage-taking and the Gerik arms heist
episode has ended bloodlessly with the surrender of the 27
perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
"This is achieved through excellent cooperation and
coordination between the police, the armed forces and the various
other agencies," Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government made no offers or deals with the arms
robbers but instead adopted a strategy of convincing them into
giving up.
</P>
<P>
However, the whole drama has claimed at least two lives as two
men who surrendered Thursday morning told the security authorities
that their gang executed two of their three hostages.
</P>
<P>
The surrender of the two Thursday morning indicated an early
end to the drama.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government Wednesday made the appeal to the group
to surrender.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen members of the group impersonating senior army officers
raided two army camps in Gerik in the Perak state on Sunday
morning and got away with a huge cache of weapons including
grenade launchers, machine guns and more than 100 assault rifles
and thousands of rounds of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
The gang was led by an ex-serviceman identified as Amin Razali
while its members included highly-qualified people such as
accountants, auditors and multi-media engineers, according to the
home minister.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the episode occurred, Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said
poor security check and weapon control system allowed
impersonators to cart away the assortment of weaponry.
</P>
<P>
The incident showed that procedures relating to security
maintenance at key installations such as weapons depot are ignored,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The security forces cordoned the area since Monday night after
the discovery of three four-wheeled-drive vehicles believed to
have been used by the weapon stealers and a combined police-
military massive manhunt tracked the weapon stealers hiding in
Sauk in the state early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The security forces called for reinforcement Tuesday morning
upon locating the group's hideout among orchards in the area.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the security forces shot and wounded one of
weapon stealers during a brief skirmish with them.
</P>
<P>
The arms heist drama came less than three months after the
abduction of 21 people by armed gunmen in Sipadan Island, off
Sabah, East Malaysia, last April. The hostage case is yet to end
as the hostage-holders are still holding 20 of them in southern
Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
