<HEADLINE> Manila Eyes Consultations on Special Powers Measure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
planning to hold consultations with various sectors of society on
a proposed measure to give the president special economic powers
to speed up rehabilitation and development efforts in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Press Secretary and Presidential Spokesman Ricardo Puno said
Thursday that the inputs from the consultations would be
considered in a draft of the Mindanao Crisis Act to be submitted
to the congress by the government.
</P>
<P>
"We'll see what we can get from the various sectors. This is
just a draft, and nothing is final at this stage," Puno said in a
radio interview.
</P>
<P>
Puno also said it is up to the congress to determine the
composition of the proposed oversight committees that would
monitor the use of these special powers.
</P>
<P>
In a separate radio interview, Executive Secretary Ronaldo
Zamora said that despite opposition from some lawmakers, the
government remains determined to push through with its bid to seek
special powers for the president to accelerate Mindanao's
development.
</P>
<P>
House Majority Leader Eduardo Gullas, on his part, said
Thursday that the congress has the last say on the scope of the
special power that can be extended and the length of time it can
be exercised, or if it should be granted at all.
</P>
<P>
Gullas said in a statement that he is inclined to favor the
granting of special powers to the government "only if it is
intended to revive the battered economy of war-torn Mindanao."
</P>
<P>
He recalled that the congress enacted the Electric Power Crisis
Act in 1993 and gave President Fidel Ramos special powers to solve
the country's energy supply problem.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the congress also enacted the Water Crisis Act to give
President Ramos emergency powers to lick the nation's water supply
crisis, he added.
</P>
<P>
"In both instances, the government was able to fast-track
implementation of vital projects that ultimately solved our power
and water problems," Gullas recalled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
