<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urbanization Improves Living Standards of Peasants (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China gives priority to the development of towns such as Dawang
and regards the growth of towns as the only way to truly modernize
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, in 1999 nearly 15 percent of the surplus laborers
who left their villages found jobs in towns and cities, 5.3
percentage points higher than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The number of urbanites now is only 30 percent of the nation's
population, less than the rate of 40 percent which is required for
the sustained economic development in the country, economists said.
</P>
<P>
China's advanced urbanization is expected to help increase the
nation's domestic demand, and support the development of township
enterprises, which are a powerful force for narrowing the economic
gap between rural and urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Township enterprises are regarded as the economic mainstay in
towns and also the key factor in boosting urbanization in the
country.
</P>
<P>
During the 1978-1999 period, township enterprises across the
country annually provided jobs for an average of six million out-
of-work peasants.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the number of laborers engaged in agricultural
production accounted for 93 percent of the nation's total
population in 1978, the year China introduced the reform and
opening-up policy, far above the current 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of workers employed in township enterprises is
estimated to rise from the current 125 million to 137 million by
2005.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urbanization Improves Living Standards of Peasants (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The migrants now earn a living by running stores and working in
township-enterprises in Dawang, seeing the move as the best way to
improve their living standards.
</P>
<P>
For years, the Chinese government tightly controlled the flow
of peasants from rural to urban areas by invoking the permanent
resident system.
</P>
<P>
Chinese peasants used to be able to improve their circumstances
by joining the military or entering university, then moving on to
cities to work and live there.
</P>
<P>
But major changes have occurred since the Chinese government
and economists realized that urbanization is key to the sustained
economic development in the country, allowing peasants to leave
rural areas for urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Urbanization helps give jobs to the surplus rural laborers, who
otherwise would be unemployed.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, an additional 3,000 villagers have resettled into
Dawang, according to local office in charge of residents'
administration.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, in Shandong Province alone, as many as three
million peasants have moved to towns and cities to work annually,
giving a big push to local economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urbanization Improves Living Standards of Peasants (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 6 (Xinhua) -- People in a remote small town in east
China's Shandong province now live a modern-day life, partly
because they have access to consumer goods like Coca-Cola and
fashionable cosmetics that were once only available in big cities.
</P>
<P>
Now on sale in a 40-sq-m supermarket in Dawang Town are
varieties of foreign-brand goods and a number of luxury items.
</P>
<P>
Yan Shousong, 39, owns the store, which is the only one in town
and provides the Yan family's sole source of income. It is
difficult to determine the social status of Yan, who was born to a
peasant family, and whose ancestors lived for generations in Yanji
Village about four km away.
</P>
<P>
Five years ago, Yan and his family moved out of the small
village and settled in Dawang, a place now seen as an ideal choice
for families seeking the good life.
</P>
<P>
"Dawang is certainly incomparable to big cities like Shanghai
and Beijing, but we could live nearly the same life as urbanites
there," Yan said.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, Dawang has been modernized with wide streets, parks,
Yan's supermarket, and entertainment centers. Its population has
risen from just 500 eight years ago to the present 10,000.
</P>
<P>
The influx of peasants from neighboring villages is mostly
responsible for Dawang's reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
