<HEADLINE> China to Involve More People in Genome Studies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- China will enroll a group of
researchers to do follow-up studies of the human genome sequencing,
said Yang Huanming, a chief scientist of the Human Genome Project
(HGP) in China today.
</P>
<P>
China has called together a large group of talented personnel
within a short time last year to complete the one percent of the
human genome sequencing.
</P>
<P>
Since the country has developed its genome sequencing capacity
to a higher level, it needs more scientific workers to continue
projects in this field, said Yang.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Genomics Institute has already worked out a plan to
provide positions for several dozens of people from home and
abroad who can either be college graduates, ordinary researchers
or senior experts in this field.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scholars who are now working overseas are also welcome
to cooperate with the institute to do relevant projects, said
Zhang Meng, a spokesman for the institute, adding that they will
also try to attract more overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
The institute has introduced 30 sequencers (gene sequencing
machine) from the United States in May, enabling the country to
have a gene sequencing capacity five times bigger than before.
</P>
<P>
The institute has already carried out some genome research
projects which include a project on hybrid super paddy rice and
another on the pig gene sequencing.
</P>
<P>
The institute now has more than 200 staff members, 70 to 80
percent of them had college education, and about one-fourth of
people have postgraduate or doctorate degrees. There are ten
research professors at the institute, half of whom are Chinese
scholars back from abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
