<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bandits Kill 18 in Northeastern Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen people were killed by
armed bandits at a hilly settlement at El-Danaba, Kenya's North
Eastern Province, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Eight other victims, mostly women and children, were seriously
injured in the raid which occurred on Wednesday morning on the
border of Wajir and Mandera districts in northeastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the attackers suspected from the
Ajuran clan, said to number over 100 and wielding rifles, raided
the settlement mainly inhabited by the Garreh and Degodia
clansmen.
</P>
<P>
Mandera District Commissioner James Seriani described the
attack as inhuman, and local police suspected the incident was a
revenge attack.
</P>
<P>
Seriani said security personnel, on learning of the attack,
repulsed the raiders who fled into Wajir North, adding that due
to ferocity of the attack, the government had to use artillery
and mortar bombs to beat off the bandits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
