<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former U.S. President Urges Nigerian Govt Branches to Work Harmoniously </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Former U. S. President Jimmy Carter
Wednesday called up Nigeria's executive and legislative branches
of government to cooperate to stabilize the nascent civil
government.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian press Thursday quoted him as saying that when people
have a feeling that their president and congress can not work
together in reasonable comfort, it opens the door for military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's top legislature, the National Assembly, has been seen
lately in constant conflicts with government led by Olusegun
Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo administration often criticizes the National Assembly
for its tardiness in passing bills of vital importance for the
country, while the country's top legislature in turn accusing
from time to time the government of acting arbitrarily.
</P>
<P>
At the same occasion, the visiting former U. S. president
extolled the qualities of Nigerians, saying that the country had
the capacity to lead Africa, if its human resources were properly
harnessed.
</P>
<P>
He said that there were about 27,000 Nigerian medical doctors
practicing in the U.S., and attributed it a clear demonstration of
how intelligent Nigerians were. 
</P>
</TEXT>
