<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AOC Stops Doping Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The probe into claims of drug
abuse among top domestic athletes came to an abrupt end on
Thursday after the whistleblower refused to give names.
</P>
<P>
Australian Olympic Committee (AOC) had appointed judge Tricia
Kavanagh to lead an independent inquiry into allegations made by
the dual Olympic discus thrower Werner Reiterer.
</P>
<P>
In his book "Positive" which was released on Wednesday,
Reiterer claimed that officials helped him avoid testing positive
to drug use.
</P>
<P>
He also alleged that swimmers and track athletes were using
illegal human growth hormones, which were undetectable through
conventional doping methods.
</P>
<P>
But the AOC gave up the investigation after the 32-year-old
refused to give names concerned.
</P>
<P>
Reiterer said during a press conference at Sydney that the
corrupt officials he knew of were either retired or were not going
to be involved in an official capacity at the upcoming Sydney
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Believing that identifying individual drugs cheats was not a
solution to the problem, Reiterer said he could not provide any
more details to investigators.
</P>
<P>
Although the AOC inquiry will not go ahead, Reiterer, who had
confessed use of steroids for five years, still faces a two-year
ban from the AOC.
</P>
<P>
The AOC said the investigation could reopen at any time
Reiterer was prepared to cooperate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, South Africa Locked in World Cup Bid Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Germany and South Africa drew level
before the final round of voting by the FIFA Executive Committee
to decide the host nation for the 2006 World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
England and Morocco, the other two candidates, crashed out
after the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
Germany and South Africa both polled 11 votes after the second
round of voting by the 24-man executive. The result after the
final round of voting will be announced by FIFA president Sepp
Blatter at 1200 GMT.
</P>
<P>
A bid needs at least 13 votes to be declared the winner. If the
vote is not decisive in the first round, the bottom team will be
eliminated and members will be asked to vote again.
</P>
<P>
Morocco were eliminated in the first round after polling just
three votes. England received five, South Africa six and Germany
10.
</P>
<P>
In the second round Germany and South Africa both polled 11
with England two and therefore out of the running.
</P>
<P>
It is widely expected that the two votes for England will now
be switched to Germany in the final round giving them a winning 13-
11 margin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
