<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Office Building to Be Auctioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The posh office building
constructed by the Ministry of Water Resources with funds
earmarked for flood control projects will go up for bidding at
public auction, China's top auditor said today.
</P>
<P>
"The State Council has decided to confiscate the building, and
the Government Offices Administration of the State Council is
organizing an auction," Li Jinhua, auditor-general of the National
Audit Office, told the ongoing session of the Standing Committee
of the National People's Congress when delivering his annual audit
report.
</P>
<P>
"The money obtained from the auction will be returned to the
central government coffer," he said.
</P>
<P>
News of the notorious case of misappropriation of state funds
by the ministry was first made public by the auditor-general in
his annual report last year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry was also found to have diverted state funds for
non-budgetary use, such as stock market speculating in 1998. So
far, 85.2 million yuan, or 71.8 percent, of the misused money has
been recovered, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Officials responsible for the unlawful acts have been given
penalties by the Ministry of Supervision, he said, without
elaborating.
</P>
<P>
Li claimed most of the other departments of the State Council
have redressed their mistakes exposed in his work report last year.
</P>
<P>
Officials and individuals in the Ministry of Finance who used
state treasury funds to start up new companies and erect new
hotels and office buildings have returned the money, according to
the auditor-general.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Taxation last year collected 72
percent of the due revenue that should have been collected in 1998,
and the customs recovered 46 percent of the due tariffs for 1998,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The State Planning Commission, Foreign Ministry and the State
Administration of Civil Aviation also paid back misappropriated
money, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
