<HEADLINE> Spain Supports Kenya's Rural Electrification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Spanish government has approved
a further credit of 770 million shillings (about 10 million U.S.
dollars) to finance Kenya's rural electrification projects across
the country, Kenyan Energy Minister Francis Lotodo has said.
</P>
<P>
Newspapers in the capital Nairobi Thursday quoted Lotodo as
saying the new credit brings to a total of 1.56 billion shillings
(about 20 million dollars) that Spain has granted to the Kenyan
government for the rural electrification.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks on Tuesday when he handed over
seven vehicles acquired with the Spanish credit to ABB Kenya Ltd.
which has been contracted to implement 32 rural electrification
projects in the first phase of the program.
</P>
<P>
Lotodo said since the inception of rural electrification, his
government had spent 4.5 billion shillings (about 60 million
dollars) on connecting 70,000 consumers to the national grid.
</P>
<P>
He said that electrification of rural areas was part of the
government's primary objective of industrialization and poverty
reduction, and called on other donors to consider financing the
program.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the French government has already committed
itself to financing part of the project in the next three years.
</P>
