<HEADLINE> Zambia to Install Satellite for Rural Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Fidelis Mando, deputy minister of
Zambian Information and Broadcasting Services, has announced that
his ministry will put up a satellite this year to ensure that all
areas in the country have radio and television coverage.
</P>
<P>
Since the program was a presidential directive, it was high on
the ministry's agenda, he was quoted as saying by Thursday's
Zambia Daily Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
He said the satellite would be mounted this year because the
current terrestrial satellite did not cater for rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Mando said because of lack of adequate satellite to transcend
terrestrial transmission, most of the areas in the country
received no television and radio coverage.
</P>
<P>
It was important that rural areas also had access to
communication through both the print and electronic media, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mando, who was speaking in an interview in Lusaka early this
week, said due to physical barriers such as mountains which
blocked the process, the current terrestrial transmission was
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
The government was not only working on the satellite but would
also install rural telephones and other better services, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mando said the satellite would be in place once the on-going
negotiations with cooperating partners were concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
