<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Hopes to Resume Talks With MILF Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Thursday that it is hopeful that it can resume peace talks with
the secessionist Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) sometime
later this month.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Orlando Mercado of the Department of National Defense
said Thursday that this was the assessment he got from chief
government negotiator Edgardo Batenga.
</P>
<P>
"I talked with General Batenga Wednesday. He said the peace
talks with the MILF will push through," Mercado said in a radio
interview.
</P>
<P>
Mercado made this clear even as he belied persistent reports
that he gave the military a deadline to overrun Camp Abubakar, the
headquarters of the MILF in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"As far as we're concerned our objective is to degrade the
military capability of the MILF. That's what we're doing now," he
said.
</P>
<P>
But Mercado also scored the MILF for its use of civilians as
human shields in protecting itself from military attacks. He
branded as an old excuse the MILF's claim that Camp Abubakar is
only a collection of communities composed mostly of civilians.
</P>
<P>
Mercado reiterated the government's position that it will not
allow the MILF to conduct harassment operations against soldiers
and civilians.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Presidential Palace said the government continues
to maintain open lines of communication and pursue back channeling
peace efforts with the MILF in its desire to secure a just and
enduring peace in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
However, the government said that the two conditions set by
President Joseph Estrada -- for the MILF to renounce its bid for
an independent Islamic state and for it to stop its terrorist and
criminal acts --- must be satisfied for the talks to progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
