<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cultural Relics News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Today's cultural relics news briefs:
</P>
<P>
 Ancient Tool Made of Antler Discovered in Ningxia
</P>
<P>
A tool made from an antler dating back to the Western Xia
Dynasty (1308-1227) was recently discovered in Haiyuan County,
northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The tool is 12.9 cm long and is carved with an image of an
animal's head. Experts said the tool was used to help untie ropes
which fastened tents.
</P>
<P>
They said that Li Yuanhao, founding emperor of the Western Xia
Dynasty, had a temporary dwelling place in Haiyuan County.
</P>
<P>
 More Relics of Han Dynasty Unearthed in Chongqing
</P>
<P>
A batch of relics from the Han Dynasty (206 B.C. - 220 A.D.)
have been unearthed at a group of Han tombs at Luozhouba, Wulong
County of Chongqing Municipality in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Among the items is a man-made money tree with a copper trunk
and copper coins hanging from its branches. The tree once stood on
a porcelain pedestal, said experts. A round mirror, with a 6.2 cm
diameter, has four birds carved on its back. Several coins from
the Eastern Han Dynasty (25-220) were also excavated at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
 Tomb of Song Dynasty Discovered in Shanxi
</P>
<P>
A wood-frame tomb chamber with an arched roof dating back to
the Song Dynasty (960-1279) was excavated at the Yanliang Village,
Pingyao County of north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 relics have been unearthed from the tomb.
</P>
<P>
In another development, a tomb of a family living during the
Jin Dynasty (1115-1234) was unearthed in Houma city of Shanxi
Province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cause of Explosion in South China Determined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Police have determined that
Monday's explosion in a water tunnel of south China's Gaohu
Reservoir was caused by a bomb planted by local people angry about
a controversial water diverting project.
</P>
<P>
Six people near the tunnel at the time of the blast died from
suffocation, said police in Puning City, Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The water diverting project, built by Daping township
government, is located on the border of Daping and the township of
Shuichun, whose residents oppose the plan.
</P>
<P>
Shuichun residents worried that the project would negatively
affect the township's irrigation and the hydro-electric power
generating.
</P>
<P>
The criminal case, which has drawn concern from the provincial
government, is under intensive investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
