<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boldon Wins 100, 200 at Lausanne Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Trinidad's Ato Boldon claimed two
titles at the Athletissima Grand Prix in Lausanne on Wednesday, by
winning both the 100 meters and 200 meters.
</P>
<P>
Boldon clocked the second-fastest time of the year with 9.95
seconds in the 100, and finished the 200 with 19.97, the third
best result this season.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 Olympic bronze medalist Boldon edged Nigeria's Francis
Obikwelu, runner-up in 9.97, and Britain's Jason Gardener, third
in 10.09.
</P>
<P>
Double Olympic champion Marie Jose Perec of France, who
competes her first race in almost year, had to settle for the
runner-up behind Debbie Ferguson of the Bahamas in the women's
200m.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson equaled the season's best time set by Australia's
Melinda Gainsford-Taylor in 22.43 seconds, while Perec, the 200
and 400 Olympic champion, came to second with 22.71.
</P>
<P>
American Allen Johnson, defending Olympic champion, post the
season's quickest time in the 110 hurdles in 13.06.
</P>
<P>
Two-time world champion Cathy Freeman of Australia recorded the
season's top performance in the women's 400 in 49.56, clinching
her 38th victory in 39 finals since the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Ekaterina Thanou won the women's 100 in 10.91, beating
Zhanna Pintusevitch to second in 0.03.
</P>
<P>
World champion Maksim Tarasov of Russia captured the gold with
a jump of 5.85 meters, ahead of American record holder Jeff
Hartwig. 
</P>
</TEXT>
