</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton will convene a summit with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat next Tuesday at Camp David, a
remote presidential retreat in Maryland, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Barak, however, immediately suffered a coalition setback when
Interior Ministry Natan Sharansky announced his resignation.
</P>
<P>
Barak had called upon his coalition partners, particularly
Yisrael Ba'aliya led by Sharansky and the National Religious Party,
to remain in the government for the time being. He said Israel will
be much better going to these crucial negotiations with as broad a
base of support as possible.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Barak said on Wednesday that he will lead the Israeli
delegation to next week's three-way summit meeting "with a heavy
sense of responsibility for the future of the Jewish people."
</P>
<P>
Barak said he would strive to "achieve separation from the
Palestinians and create relations of good neighbors with them,
while maintaining our red lines."
</P>
<P>
During his just-concluded trip to Europe, Barak told reporters "
Even if I stay with nine (cabinet) ministers and one quarter of the
Knesset (parliament) behind me, we will do it."
</P>
<P>
President Clinton of the U.S. acknowledged there were "no easy
answers and certainly no painless ones." He said an attempt would
be made to reach an agreement before September 13 - when the
interim agreement expires and the Palestinians may declare an
independent state.
</P>
