<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Lawmakers Propose Inspection of Prisons: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Iranian lawmakers have proposed to
inspect the prisons around the country in a bid to "better protect
the legal rights of the inmates," local media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
There may be violations of standards or trampling of rights in
prisons, so "we are going to send a delegation to check into the
cases," said Musavi Khoeini, a reformist deputy from Tehran and
co-sponsor of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Khoeini cited as an example in point the case of Akbar Ganji, a
reformist journalist who was jailed in April on charges of
violating Islamic values and principles and advocating U.S.-style
reforms. Ganji was said to have been mistreated and was not allowed
to contact his family.
</P>
<P>
Ganji was able to make himself heard, but there may be a lot of
others in prisons who are hardly known and are unable to voice
their grievances, Khoeini said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Majlis has the right to supervise government
departments, including the conservative-controlled Judiciary which
in the past few months closed some 18 reformist papers and journals
and sent a number of reformist journalist into prison.
</P>
<P>
The tension between reformists and the conservative
establishment heightened following the February 18 parliamentary
elections, which resulted in the overwhelming victory of reformers
supporting President Mohammad Khatami's liberal programs.
</P>
<P>
Although reformers have absolute control in the new parliament,
which started work on May 27, their power is limited, as all bills
passed by the legislative body have to be approved by the
conservative Guardians Council. The conservatives also control many
other key state organs, including the military.
</P>
<P>
Khoeini, a member of the reformist Islamic Iran Participation
Front, said a parliamentary delegation would be sent to all
official prisons of the country after the proposal was approved by
the Majlis.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the delegation could be dispatched before the
Majlis' summer vacation which begins on July 22 and lasts for 15
days.
</P>
<P>
On the possible reaction from the judiciary to the proposal,
Khoeini said the Judiciary should welcome the initiative.
Otherwise, "the ambiguities in the public opinion would be
increased," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
