<HEADLINE> East Timor Leader Acknowledges Challenge Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- East Timor leader Xanana Gusmao
said here Thursday his country still faces difficult challenges as
it moves towards independence next year.
</P>
<P>
Gusmao, in New Zealand for a six-day visit, made the remark
when he was briefing a New Zealand parliamentary select committee
on the current situation and future prospects for his country.
</P>
<P>
Last September saw the people of East Timor vote overwhelmingly
for independence in a UN sponsored referendum after 24 years of
occupation by Indonesian forces.
</P>
<P>
Gusmao said his country was facing a difficult challenge as it
moves towards its first general elections, which may be held in
August next year.
</P>
<P>
"Full independence will not be an easy job as East Timorese
haven't had experience in decision-making or held positions in
high government," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the most immediate issues are to address the crimes
against humanity and dealing with the problem of refugees still in
West Timor.
</P>
<P>
Gusmao said East Timor appreciates the help and assistance it
has been receiving from the international community, but is aiming
for self sufficiency and wants to develop relationships based on
mutual cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said his country is weighing up the advantages and
disadvantages of belonging to either the Association of South East
Asian Nations (ASEAN) or the Pacific Forum. But he indicated his
country is interested in joining a forum of small countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
