<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealanders Deeper in Debt Mire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- New Zealanders are sinking into
more and more debt, with household liabilities more than doubling
in the 10 years, the Evening Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted figures released by the
New Zealand central bank, Reserve Bank, as showing that household
debt as a percentage of personal disposable income remained at
about 50 percent between 1978 and 1987. It then started to climb,
hitting 100 percent in 1997 and is now at about 111 percent.
</P>
<P>
That means that even if every New Zealander put every cent of
their earnings for one year into paying off their loans, they
still wouldn't be debt-free.
</P>
<P>
In the five years to December 1999, household borrowing
increased by 30 billion NZ dollars (14.1 billion U.S. dollars) or
70 percent. A factor is the introduction of tertiary loans for
students last decade, which now make up 4 percent of total
household debt.
</P>
<P>
"As we've borrowed more, we've saved less. In 1981 we saved 11
percent of our income; in 1998 our savings rate fell below 0
percent for the first time, which means we're not saving anything
at all," the paper quoted Reserve Bank economist Clive Thorp as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
