<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Wealth Inquiry Commission Formed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian House of
Representatives (DPR) officially endorsed here Thursday the
establishment of the Inquiry Commission on State Official's Wealth
in a plenary session presided over by its Deputy Speaker Tosari
Widjaya.
</P>
<P>
The commission consists 45 members from various groups
including the Indonesian Military (TNI), Non-governmental
organizations, bureaucrats, lawyers and politicians.
</P>
<P>
All members of the commission have underwent fit and proper
test which was conducted by the House Commission II on domestic
and legal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The names were also screened from a list of 204 candidates
proposed by President Abdurrahman Wahid and public proposals.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of the commission is in line with the
government spirit to combat rampant corruption, collusion and
nepotistic practices in the country," Widjaya told the session.
</P>
<P>
"The commission will be fully backed up by the House. And the
House has also recommended to the government to provide facilities
and funds to the commission," Widjaya added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, House Speaker Akbar Tandjung said that the commission
would have one chairman, four deputy chairmen, and 40 members
tasked with auditing officials of state institutions and state-
owned companies.
</P>
<P>
After the passage, all the commission members will be sworn by
President Abdurrahman Wahid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
