<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Wildfires Still Burn in U.S. Colorado </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Three wildfires in western
Colorado were burning out of control Wednesday, scorching more
than 13,100 acres, local officials reported.
</P>
<P>
The Cone Mountain fire 60 kilometers southwest of Grand
Junction, Colorado, has consumed 3,300 acres and has quadrupled in
size since it was detected on Monday, said Bill Kight, spokesman
for the U.S. Forest Service Interagency Dispatch Center.
</P>
<P>
Access to the rugged site has hampered firefighting efforts,
and the fire is threatening three homes and several historical
mining-camp structures, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kight said firefighters from local state and federal agencies
are on site, fighting against the wildfire. Meanwhile, they also
battled two other wildfires on Colorado's northwest plateau near
the Utah border.
</P>
<P>
The largest blaze, the Buster Flats fire in the Dinosaur
National Monument, has burned 9,000 acres since it erupted Monday.
Authorities have ordered local residents to evacuate to the nearby
Gates of Ladore and Brown's National Wildlife Refuge campgrounds
as a precautionary measure.
</P>
<P>
The most recent blaze, the Klinger fire 30 kilometers southwest
of Rangley ignited sometime Tuesday and has consumed 800 acres by
late Wednesday afternoon, said Robin Sill, spokeswoman for the
Craig Interagency Dispatch Center.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the cause of the blazes was unknown.
</P>
<P>
The fire season is shaping up as the worst since 1996,
according to the National Interagency Fire Center in Idaho. It
began more than a month ago with blazes engulfing areas of Florida
and the Southwest, most notably in Los Alamos, New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
About 44,300 fires covering more than 1.2 million acres have
been recorded nationwide so far, with drought getting worse in the
West. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Latinos Still Get Low Wages Despite Booming Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A report released here said
Wednesday that while the booming economy provided a lift for many
American workers, Hispanics earned half what whites did in 1998,
with many stuck in low-paying jobs that offered little promise of
advancement.
</P>
<P>
A growing but poorer Hispanic work force could hurt the
nation's ability to compete globally and fund government programs
such as Social Security, said Sonia Perez, a labor researcher for
the National Conference of La Raza and editor of the 230-page
report.
</P>
<P>
"This isn't about being nice to Latino people. This is about
America's future and our best interests as a nation," said Perez.
The report was released at La Raza's annual conference.
</P>
<P>
La Raza President Raul Yzaguirre said an increase in the number
of part-time and low-skill jobs has played a part in keeping
Latinos in lower paying jobs. But he said such factors are not
unique to the Latino community.
</P>
<P>
"There was a time when a strong back and an ability to read and
write would mean a good job in the manufacturing sector,"
Yzaguirre said. "That is no longer the case. Now we are seeing
extremely well-paying jobs or very low paying jobs."
</P>
<P>
Latinos face other barriers to better jobs, including having
less education compared to whites and blacks, said Perez. She said
more federal funding should be allocated to programs like Head
Start, in which Hispanics are underrepresented nationally.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income for Hispanics rose 4.5 percent to 11,434 U.S.
dollars in 1998, while per capita income for blacks rose 3.3
percent to 12,957 dollars and white per capita earnings rose 3.2
percent to 22,952 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The median income for Hispanic married-couple families was 34,
816 dollars, compared to 54,736 dollars for white families.
</P>
