<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lankans Warned Against Vulnerability to HIV/AIDS  By Lian Guohui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankans, especially migrant
workers and military personnel, have been warned against
vulnerability to Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) or Acquired
Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS) despite a low prevalence in this
South Asian island country.
</P>
<P>
The warning comes as some 178 countries are preparing to send
delegates to attend the 13th World AIDS Conference which is due to
be held in Durban, South Africa from July 9. The week-long
conference will focus on breaking the silence over the disease
which has killed millions, according to conference organizers.
</P>
<P>
The first HIV/AIDS positive case in Sri Lanka was reported in
1987. Since then the number of those infected has been increasing.
The United Nations has estimated that at present there are up to 8,
000 Sri Lankans who are infected with HIV, and warns that the
number could increase 10-fold over the next five years if no
action is taken.
</P>
<P>
While Sri Lanka is seen as a low prevalence country at present,
medical experts and other academics here said the disease could
spread rapidly due to Sri Lanka's proximity to India, the high
number of Sri Lankans working abroad, long-running civil war and
lack of awareness.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Tudor Silva of Sri Lanka's prestigious University of
Peradeniya said one of the main factors that contribute to the
vulnerability is Sri Lanka's proximity to India, which is "soon to
become an epicenter for transmission of HIV/AIDS."
</P>
<P>
According to the United Nations, one quarter of the some 31
million people infected worldwide live in Asia and India is now
the country with the largest number of people living with HIV/AIDS
in the world.
</P>
<P>
Although Asia has avoided a large-scale epidemic, a cooperation
action is needed to halt its spread as Asian developing countries
"cannot afford the human and financial toll of an AIDS epidemic,"
Vice-President of World Bank for South Asia region Meiko Nishimizu
told the fifth international conference on AIDS in Asia held in
Kuala Lumpur in October, 1999.
</P>
<P>
In Sri Lanka's battle against HIV/AIDS, migrant workers and
military personnel have been identified as new high risk groups as
large numbers of women seek employment abroad and the ethnic civil
war drags into the 17th year.
</P>
<P>
The migrant workers are important for this cash-starved Indian
Ocean island. Sri Lankans working abroad have topped the list of
foreign exchange earners in recent years, sending home 923 million
U.S. dollars in 1999. According to the Sri Lanka Bureau of Foreign
Employment, the total number of Sri Lankan workers abroad is
estimated to be around 788,000, of whom 65 percent are females
mostly as housemaids. Some housemaids are sexually exploited by
their employers.
</P>
<P>
Health officials expressed fear that the large number of Sri
Lankan workers returning from abroad might be bringing the deadly
disease with them. They said they were planning to carry out large-
scale AIDS prevention measures, including blood-testing in the
country.
</P>
<P>
At least five HIV-positive cases have been identified early
this year. All of them had been affected while they were abroad.
The latest two victims were detected when they came for treatment
complaining of phlegm and fever. One victim, a married woman, had
recently returned from Germany and the other, was a 23-year-old
youth who returned from Bangkok after three years.
</P>
<P>
Apart from external threats, Sri Lanka faces internal war
situation which leaves the country vulnerable to HIV/AIDS. Large
number of soldiers have been stationed in Sri Lanka's north and
east to fight Tamil Tiger rebels who are waging a war to carve out
a separate homeland called Eelam since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers, who are separated from their families and normal
society, are the perfect target for the commercial sex trade. "It
is only natural that a sex industry gets established," said Prof.
Silva.
</P>
<P>
He added that soldiers are not the only group made vulnerable
by the war, wives of soldiers and war widows face similar problems.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey to gauge awareness among young people about HIV/
Aids revealed teenagers are mostly ignorant about the killer
disease. Some even believe that the HIV virus is transmitted by
mosquitoes, swimming, kissing, sharing cups and plates, wearing
each-other's clothes, handling money and hugging. In many schools
in Sri Lanka, AIDS is a "four-letter" word -- that is taboo to
talk about.
</P>
<P>
To create awareness among young people, the AIDS Coalition for
Care, Education and Support Services (ACCESS), a top non-
governmental group involved in AIDS/HIV education, has launched a
"Youth for AIDS awareness" project.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Kamalika Abeyratne, chairwoman of ACCESS, said one of the
main problems faced by those HIV/AIDS sufferers was isolation.
</P>
<P>
"Make one small mistake with this deadly virus - in my case the
mistake was not even mine - and you will suddenly find that you
have become less than human," she said, who being a practicing
doctor was infected by a contaminated needle.
</P>
<P>
To counter the emerging menace of HIV/AIDS spread, Sri Lanka
launched its first telephone counseling service on HIV/AIDS in
March this year. The AIDS helpline, which is open four hours a day,
was funded by the Australian Agency for International Development.
</P>
<P>
The new helpline, which is staffed by volunteers, is aimed at
preventing the spread of HIV and AIDS as well as making contact
with those already affected and their families by offering
information and support.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said the helpline is only a first step. They said
the spread of HIV/AIDS in Sri Lanka can be stopped only if
everyone takes responsibility and prevention -- including public
awareness of safe sex -- should be given top priority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
