<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Plans Land Reclamation in Bengal Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is seeking foreign
assistance for land reclamation in the Bay of Bengal in the wake
of fast depletion of agriculture land in the country, an official
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
As farmlands are shrinking by an astounding rate of one million
hectares per decade, the government finds land reclamation the
only effective way to face the emerging problem of food insecurity,
Senior Information Officer of the Ministry of Agriculture AKM
Neserudding Bhuiyan told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government is seeking foreign aid and
investment for land reclamation in the Bay because the country's
food production would decrease as time goes on due to land
scarcity, despite increased productivity per hectare.
</P>
<P>
Every day the country is losing 221 hectares of cropland owing
to industrialization, urbanization and river erosion.
</P>
<P>
However, the government is hopeful about emergence of a huge
chunk of fertile land from land reclamation in the Bay of Bengal
and that may be as big as Bangladesh is. Bangladesh has to explore
the possibility and it needs money for reclamation from the donor
countries.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the area of cropland was more
or less static at around nine million hectares from the mid-1960s
to mid-1980s. However, in the last one decade over one million
hectares of cropland disappeared.
</P>
<P>
With the pressing needs for urbanization and infrastructure
development, more agricultural land will have to be sacrificed in
the years to come.
</P>
<P>
The country would have to grow an additional five to six
million tones of foodgrain by 2020 in a land area two million
hectares smaller than what it is now to feed the country's
population of 173 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
