<HEADLINE> International Deals Outpace U.S. Domestic Merger Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The global merger market
outpaced the downtrodden U.S. market in the first half of 2000, a
leading data firm said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of this year, the value of
international deals climbed 25 percent to 1.85 trillion dollars,
while domestic deals raised to 875.6 billion dollars, a 2.7
percent gain, according to preliminary data from Thomson Financial
Securities Data Publishing.
</P>
<P>
Globally, the number of deals in the first half of the year
grew 5 percent to 17,609, but the number of U.S. deals in the
first half of 2000 slipped 12 percent to 4,982 from 5,661 for the
same period in 1999, Thomson Financial said.
</P>
<P>
"The international M&AMP;A cycle is a bit younger than the U.S.,"
said J. Squire Junger, head of mergers and acquisition and
integration services for Arthur Andersen's Western region. "We're
seeing more Euro companies adopt more of an acquisitive attitude
as a corporate growth strategy."
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications, buoyed by French Telecom's 40 billion-
dollar acquisition of Orange, emerged as the top sector in the
first half, producing 650 deals valued at 200.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The AOL-Time Warner 182 billion-dollar merger helped the motion
picture industry climb to second place with 145 deals raising 193.
5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
And, Unilever PLC's 20.3 billion-dollar deal for Best Foods
propelled the food sector to third place with 3,684 deals valued
at 143.2 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
