<HEADLINE> Nepal Tightens Security at Nepal-India Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Security has been beefed up at
the Nepal-India Customs post in Birgunj, about 600 km Southwest of
Kathmandu, to check the growing cross-border irregularities, the
Kathmandu Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Police was compelled to tighten vigilance at the border posts
due to the growing cases of abduction, unauthorized arms
intrusions and other cross border crimes in the busy metros in
Birgunj and other parts of Parsa district that borders India's
Bihar state, a District Police Office source was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It is done to ensure the law and order situation in the
district," said Superintendent of Police Krishna Karmacharya. "If
other districts bordering India follow our initiative, the cross
border crimes could be substantially curbed."
</P>
<P>
Nepal and India have 1,700 km long open border which encourages
cross-border crimes and irregularities.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has a strong law regarding the cross border crime. If
anyone is found sneaking into the country with unauthorized arms,
the person will get two-year imprisonment. But due to lax security
screening at the border posts, the laws hardly have any practical
significance.
</P>
<P>
Police estimates that one out of every 20 households and one
out of every 50 persons in Parsa district carry unauthorized arms,
most for self-defense and rest for their vested interests.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll conducted recently by a media house of Nepal
revealed that 85.5 percent of Nepalese want the Nepal-India border
regulated and almost 50 percent want passport system to be
introduced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
