<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Cuts Import Tariffs of 542 Items of Industrial Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Thailand on Thursday cut import
tariffs of 542 items of industrial products in order to help
reduce production costs and boost the country's export
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
"The reduction will also help reduce costs to consumers and
support economy recovery," Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanahaeminda was quoted by a government source as saying
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Most of those industrial goods, whose tariffs are now reduced
from 5-30 percent to 0-10 percent, are raw materials unavailable
locally, including primary products, intermediate factors of
production, machinery and other goods.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the tariff cuts will cost the country
revenues of 3.3 billion baht (85 million U.S. dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
However, Tarrin said, this could be compensated by rising
revenues of income and value-added taxes, as producers could gain
more profits due to lower production costs and increasing sale
volumes.
</P>
<P>
The move is also believed to help boost Thai exports to
regional and world markets, and is in line with the Association of
Southeast Asia Nations' free trade agreement, he stated.
</P>
<P>
Local industry executives welcomed the reductions, saying it
will reduce distortions in which some raw materials were taxed at
a higher rate than finished products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
