<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, UNTAET Agree to Form Timor Border Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesia government and the
United Nations Transitional Administration in East Timor (UNTAET)
have agreed to establish a joint committee that will determine the
definitive border between East Timor and West Timor (East Nusa
Tenggara province of Indonesia).
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the third round of border
negotiations between Indonesia and UNTAET which ended in Surabaya,
capital of Indonesia's East Java province, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a press statement issued by the Foreign Affairs
Ministry, the Joint Border Committee will discuss the border and
examine a border convention that was signed by the Netherlands and
Portugal on October 1, 1904. The committee will also discuss
relevant international regulations.
</P>
<P>
"It has been agreed that the final decision on the border must
be approved by the Indonesian government and the next
administration in East Timor," the press statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said Indonesia rejected a UNTAET proposal to give East Timor
road access to the Oecussi enclave through Jakarta-controlled West
Timor.
</P>
<P>
"This rejection is based on security considerations and rules
of law, but also because the streets are impossible (to pass),"
the statement was quoted by the Indonesian Observer Thursday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the East Timorese administration "did not object" to
accepting Jakarta's offer to allow Oecussi and the rest of East
Timor to be connected by sea routes.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day meeting, the Indonesian delegation was led by
the Foreign Affairs Ministry's Director of International
Organization Sudjadnan Purnohadingrat, while the United Nations
was represented by Peter Glabraith of the UNTAET.
</P>
<P>
"The negotiations are to follow up on a joint communique issued
by Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab and Special Deputy to the United
Nations Secretary General Sergio Vieira de Mello on February 9,
2000," Sudjatnan said.
</P>
<P>
Sudjadnan added that six problems had been discussed on the
basis of the joint communique including the establishment of an
Indonesian representative office in Dili (East Timor), the opening
of a UNTAET office in Jakarta, and a UNTAET liaison office in
Kupang (capital of East Nusa Tenggara), and finding a solution to
issues relating to the transfer of power, such as state assets,
archives on East Timor, demarcation, pensioners and others.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are scheduled to meet again in Bukittingi, West
Sumatra, in early September to discuss various issues.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, voted for independence
from Indonesia's rule on August 30 last year. The territory,
currently administered by the U.N., is expected to hold its first
general elections in autumn next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
