<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Vietnam Continues to Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment inflows into
Vietnam in the first six months of this year fell by 35 percent to
520 million U.S. dollars against the same period last year,
according to a report of the latest issue of Vietnam Investment
Review (VIR).
</P>
<P>
Although the number of newly-licensed projects rose by 20
percent to 140, the pledged capital fell to 390 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Investment pledges for 55 existing foreign-invested enterprises
stood at 130 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Most of the new project licenses were issued by the country's
local government authorities and the 54 industrial zone and export
processing zone management boards.
</P>
<P>
VIR said that "foreign investment in Vietnam has dropped
steadily in recent years. The foreign investors complain of high
business costs, excessive red tape and falling returns on
investment."
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Ministry of Planing and Investment is considering
decentralizing its authority in a bid to boost investment by
allowing provincial cities to approve investment projects worth up
to 10 million dollars from the current 5 million dollars, VIR
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
