<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Lanka's Rupee Devalues to Maintain Export Competitiveness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's National Chamber of
Exporters (NCE) said that last month's snap devaluation of the
rupee against the dollar was to maintain the country's export
competitiveness and counter the increase in the current account
deficit, the Daily News reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Consequently export earnings in rupee terms could increase,
provided exporters maintained present price levels and sales
volumes in international market, the NCE sources were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan exporters had already come under pressure by foreign
buyers to reduce prices of certain export products. The
devaluation would then maintain their market shares by reducing
prices.
</P>
<P>
On the impact of devaluation, the sources said if the
elasticity of demand is high, they could be in a position to
increase volume and earn a higher sales turnover.
</P>
<P>
All products would enjoy these benefits in general irrespective
of whether the export product had a higher or low content of
imported raw material. However, products with a higher domestic
value addition would enjoy greater benefits.
</P>
<P>
The NEC had long pressed for devaluation to encourage growth in
the export sector, but were also concerned about the burden
imposed on other sectors of society.
</P>
<P>
The prices of imported products will increase as a result of
the devaluation, said the sources, adding that This in turn will
push up the general price level since the economy is highly import
dependent.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lanka's national Central Bank announced on June 20 that
it would allow the depreciation of the Sri Lankan rupee by
allowing a wider rupee-dollar trading band to boost the flagging
exports.
</P>
<P>
The spread between its buying and selling rates for the U.S.
dollar was widened by five percent from the earlier two percent.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the bank's announcement the rupee fell to 78 to the
dollar and fell further to 79.4 on June 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Animals Bred in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A total of 43.5 million of animals
were bred in Myanmar in the fiscal year 1999-2000 which ended in
March, 7 million more than the previous year, official newspaper
The New Light of Myanmar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of the animals, 3.9 million of pigs were bred in the fiscal
year, 200,000 more than the previous year in number.
</P>
<P>
During the 1999-2000, a total of 378,160 tons of meat, 1.9
billion of eggs and 650,370 tons of milk were produced, 68,460
tons, 420 million tons, 71,720 tons more than the previous year
respectively, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meat, egg and milk production are respectively projected at 386,
310 tons, 1.97 billion tons and 674,820 tons for 2000-2001 which
began in April.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's livestock and fisheries sector is the fourth largest
contributor to the country's gross domestic products after
agriculture, trade and industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's per capita meat
consumption is 6.2 kilograms annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
