<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moldovan Parliament Passes Law for Election of President by Deputies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Moldovan parliament voted
Wednesday by an overwhelming majority in favor of a constitutional
amendment allowing deputies, rather than the public, to elect the
president, Moldovan state media in Chisinau reported.
</P>
<P>
The amendment was approved by 90 out of the 101 deputies in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
To become fully effective, the new law needs to be endorsed by
President Petru Lucinschi.
</P>
<P>
The law would take effect on January 15, 2001, when Lucinschi's
mandate ends.
</P>
<P>
Lucinschi criticized the vote, saying the power increase of
parliament would lead to a political crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
If he vetoes the change, lawmakers said, they will vote again
to force him to accept it.
</P>
<P>
The vote is a blow for Lucinschi, who has been trying to
increase his own power through constitutional amendments since he
took office in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
Moldova was part of neighboring Romania until 1940, when it was
annexed by the Soviet Union under a treaty between Nazi Germany
and the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of its 4.3 million people are of Romanian descent,
and the languages in both countries are identical. 
</P>
</TEXT>
