<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's GDP to Grow by 3-4 Percent in Second Half of 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesia's central bank, Bank
Indonesia, has projected that the country's gross domestic product
(GDP will grow by between 3 and 4 percent in both second and third
quarters this year.
</P>
<P>
But, although the economy will enjoy up to 3 to 4 percent
growth, it will be faced with a number of heavy problems in the
third quarter, local leading newspapers Thursday quoted a reported
issued by the bank.
</P>
<P>
The biggest problems Indonesia has to face are the strong
inflation pressures and the weakening of exchange rate of rupiah,
the report added.
</P>
<P>
"The government's plan to raise prices of fuel and salaries of
civil servants and the police in the next few months is set to
raise the inflation rate this year," said the report, adding that
it is worried that the continuing inflation pressure will surpass
its fiscal 2000 target of 5 to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report also sees the flow of base money which continues to
move above the indicative target as a problem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it seems that the rupiah will continue to fall as it
hit a 16-month low when it closed at 9,385 per U.S. dollar on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government set the exchange rate of rupiah in current
fiscal year at 7,000 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that the continuing fall of rupiah has
something to do with the current political instability in the
country.
</P>
<P>
A bomb exploded at the attorney general office (AGO) on Tuesday
and two other bombs were also founded the following day at the
same building causing fears that the political terror would impede
economic recovery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
