<HEADLINE> Cote d'Ivoire Junta and Mutinous Soldiers Reach Deal, Curfew lifted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABIDJAN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The military regime reached an
agreement Wednesday with mutinous young soldiers to end an army
unrest.
</P>
<P>
Captain Henri Sama, Minister of Communications of the ruling
National Committee of Public Salvation, announced here that the
crisis was over and the dusk-to-dawn curfew that had been imposed
the night before in the commercial capital of Cote d'Ivoire and
some other cities in the west African country will be lifted.
</P>
<P>
In December, junior soldiers staged a coup, the first since the
country's independence from France in 1960. Their demanding a
bonus for their role in the coup was reportedly behind Tuesday's
army unrest.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Sama called on people to return to work and
assured them of resumption of public traffic Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He warned against criminal activities such as looting and
robbery. Anybody who takes advantage of the curfew lifting and
harms public security would be severely punished, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
