<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Agriculture Ministers Reach New Deal on Farm Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Canadian agriculture ministers have
reached a new deal of 5.5 billion Canadian dollars (about 3.7
billion U.S. dollars) on farm safety programs, federal Agriculture
Minister Lyle Vanclief announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Federal and provincial agriculture ministers agreed Tuesday at
their annual meeting in Fredericton, New Brunswick, that Ottawa
provides 3.3 billion dollars (about 2.2 billion U.S. dollars) and
the provinces add another 2.2 billion (about 1.5 billion U.S.
dollars) to establish a framework for farm stability over three
years, Vanclief said.
</P>
<P>
The amount of money in each province varies according to the
size of the agriculture industry.
</P>
<P>
An annual 225 million dollars (about 151 million U.S. dollars)
will go to Canada's most populous province Ontario, which makes up
almost 25 percent of agriculture and food production in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In New Brunswick, Ottawa is expected to contribute 5.3 million
dollars (about 3.6 million U.S. dollars), while the province's
share is estimated at 3 million (about 2 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The ministers are yet to work out detailed programs to
compensate farmers devastated by natural catastrophes caused by
floods, drought or vagaries of markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
