<HEADLINE> Shanghai Leukemia Sufferer Draws Public Attention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese collage student is
suffering from leukemia. If he has no money for medical treatments,
he will die.
</P>
<P>
People are trying their best to help Ding Jian, a 20-year-old
student in Shanghai-based Fudan University.
</P>
<P>
In June last year, Ding felt his eyesight was worsening, and
medical check-ups have shown that he was suffering from leukemia.
</P>
<P>
Marrow suitable for Ding must be found to save him. After
months of search, doctors found that two young people from Taiwan,
both aged 21, have marrow matching for Ding.
</P>
<P>
However, Ding from a common family in Jinhua, east China's
Zhejiang Province, is short of 250,000 yuan (about 30,000 U.S.
dollars) to undergo operation.
</P>
<P>
Students and teachers at Fudan University have made donations.
Other people have also provided assistance after they learnt Ding'
s story from media reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seasonal Floods Threaten </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Seasonal floods, mostly in mountain
regions, have caused at least 400 deaths since the beginning of
the rainy season in China, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
"As far as I know, at least 400 people have reportedly died in
floods or resulting landslides," the English language paper quoted
an official from the State flood-control department as saying.
</P>
<P>
The estimated death toll does not include ten other people
washed away by mountain torrents on Monday in the city of Dazhou
in Sichuan Province. The floods in Dazhou have caused an estimated
133 million yuan (16 million US dollars) in damages.
</P>
<P>
Local governments, especially those in northern regions that
have been suffering from drought, were urged to closely monitor
the rising water levels of rain-swollen rivers to prepare for
floods. China's peak flood season runs from late July to early
August.
</P>
<P>
Of China's existing 80,000 reservoirs, 25 percent have
dangerous sections, experts said, warning that disasters could
ensue if incidents occurred at these reservoirs in flood season.
</P>
<P>
The season's first flood peak on the Yangtze river has, since
Tuesday, entered Hubei Province in central China with a massive
waterflow of 50,000 cubic meters per second.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Control Experts Meet in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The third Asian Control Conference,
one of the world's largest international meetings of academics in
this field, began in Shanghai Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 scholars and experts in the field of automation
and control participated in the event. Over half of the
participants were from overseas.
</P>
<P>
The conference, entitled "21st Century-Oriented Automatic
Technology," will focus on the cutting edge of control theory and
new ideas and applications for automatic systems.
</P>
<P>
A major task of the conference is to emphasize the role of
automatic control in society and the development of new
technologies.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very important conference that will allow for the
exchange of technology and information about control theory and
its applications," today's "China Daily" quoted Zheng Yufan,
chairman of the conference, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Among the more than 800 papers submitted to conference
organizers, 597 were chosen to be presented during the 103
sessions of the conference.
</P>
<P>
The first and second conferences were held in Tokyo in 1994 and
Seoul in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
