<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts Put into Stabilizing Bitten City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Five days after the explosion at a
fireworks plant in Jiangmen of south China's Guangdong Province,
local efforts are turning from the rescue operation to cope with
the explosion's aftermath and ways to prevent an accident like
this from happening again.
</P>
<P>
So far, all 33 victims have been identified and nearly 50 that
were injured have been treated and released from the hospital,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Over 130 factories in the city have bee carefully inspected to
check their fire prevention facilities. As a result, 25 were
closed down and another 20 were ordered to make immediate
improvements.
</P>
<P>
He Xiansong, vice-mayor of Jiangmen, said Wednesday that the
families of the victims have calmed down and moved their attention
to the compensation plan.
</P>
<P>
The Ping'an Insurance Co. of China and the Life Insurance Co.
of China also made a public notice Wednesday urging the residents
and businesses that reported and claimed damages to "help the
enterprises recover production and the injured get healthy as soon
as possible."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, to protect residents from being infected with
diseases that may hit due to the hot steamy weather, the local
epidemic prevention department has sterilized the explosion site,
as well as the neighborhood within a radius of several hundred
meters.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Ministry of Public Security said that it's
still too early to determine the cause of the explosion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gathering Marks Discovery of Dunhuang Library Cave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A grand gathering was held here
this morning in the Great Hall of the People to mark the
centennial of the discovery of Dunhuang Library Cave.
</P>
<P>
The gathering, sponsored by the Ministry of Culture, the Gansu
provincial government and the State Administration of Cultural
Heritage, is a major event of the country's two-month
commemoration of the world-stunning find.
</P>
<P>
In 1900, Wang Yuanlu, a Taoist priest, discovered a cave at
Mogao Grottoes in Dunhuang containing more than 50,000 sutras,
documents and paintings of nearly 10 dynasties ranging from the
4th to the 11th century.
</P>
<P>
On the route of the famous Silk Road in northwest China, the
Mogao Grottoes maintain one of the world's largest art gallery for
delicate frescoes, sculptures and ancient architecture.
</P>
<P>
A large exhibition on the Dunhuang art is now going on at the
Museum of the Chinese History. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
