<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0015 GMT, July 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Interior Minister Natan Sharansky
Wednesday announced the resignation of his party, Yisrael Ba'aliya,
from the coalition government of Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Sharansky made the announcement just after U.S. President Bill
Clinton announced at the White House earlier in the day a summit
between himself, Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat will
be held next Tuesday in the United States. (Israel-Government)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Ugandan forces have completed their
withdrawal from Kisangani, the third largest city in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), a United Nations spokesman
said here.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. spokesman, Manoel de Almeida e Silva, told a press
conference here that the Ugandan troops left the DRC city by
Tuesday. (UN-Uganda-DRC)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton announced Wednesday
that he will host a summit with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat at Camp Davis, Maryland,
early next week in a bid to deal with difficult core issues on the
Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
"The objective (of the summit) is to reach an agreement on the
core issues that have fueled a half century of conflict between
Israelis and Palestinians," Clinton said at a White house briefing.
(US-Mideast)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- The assembly of Japan's southernmost island prefecture
of Okinawa on Wednesday adopted a resolution protesting at the
recent alleged molesting of a 14-year-old girl by an Okinawa-based
U.S. Marine, the Kyodo News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
The assembly unanimously approved the resolution demanding the
Japanese and U.S. governments take measures to prevent recurrence
of such incidents and apply strict discipline to U.S. soldiers,
the report said. (Okinawa-Protest-US Army)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DUSHANBE -- The presidents from China, Tajikistan, Russia,
Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan started their annual summit meeting here
Wednesday to discuss regional and international issues of common
concern and explore new ways for furthering bilateral and
multilateral cooperation among the five nations.
</P>
<P>
President of the host country, Emomali Rakhmonov, presided over
the meeting, commonly known as the "Shanghai Five" summit. (
Dushanbe-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Cote d'Ivoire imposed a curfew Tuesday evening after
troops took to the streets, firing in the air and demanding money
from the ruling military junta for their part in the December 24
coup, reports from Abidjan said.
</P>
<P>
The curfew will run from 7:00 p.m. (1900 GMT) until 6:00 a.m. (
0600 GMT). (Cote d'Ivoire-Curfew)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BOGOTA -- Over one ton of cocaine was seized Tuesday by
Colombian Police from an extreme-right paramilitary group in
Cuenca Valley, southeast department of the country, official
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Five men were held for smuggling the drug, found at a rural
zone in Yambo, close to Cali, over 530 kilometers away from
Colombia's capital. (Colombia-Cocaine)  
</P>
