<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras and Agassi on Course to Wimbledon Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Top two seeds Pete Sampras and Andre
Agassi are well staying on course for the Wimbledon tennis final
with respective victories in quarter-finals here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reigning champion and top seed Sampras, who is now within two
wins of a record 13th Grand Slam title, defeated fellow American
Jan-Michael Gambill 6-4, 6-7, 6-4, 6-4 while second seed Agassi
crushed 10th seeded Australian Mark Philippousis 7-6, 6-3 and 6-4
in the cloudy day.
</P>
<P>
In the semi-finals, Sampras will meet Belarussian qualifier
Vladimir Voltchkov and Agassi takes on another Australian 12th
seed Pat Rafter.
</P>
<P>
Sampras was made to work for his victory by the 23-year-old
Gambill who was making his first appearance in a Grand Slam
quarter-final and had defeated seventh seed Lleyton Hewitt in the
first round and number nine Thomas Enqvist on his way to the last
eight.
</P>
<P>
Gambill briefly led after taking the second set on a tie-break
7-4 but failed to break Sampras's serve once in the match and the
defending champion eventually wore his opponent down to win in two
hours 46 minutes on center court.
</P>
<P>
Voltchkov became the first qualifier since John McEnroe in 1977
to reach a Wimbledon men's semifinal when he squeezed past
Zimbabwe's Byron Black 7-6, 7-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Neither Voltchkov nor Black played anything like inspired
tennis, squandering leads and swapping service breaks regularly
and each finding it difficult to serve out a set.
</P>
<P>
Rafter beat German Alexander Popp 6-3, 6-2, 7-6 on Court One.
The twice U.S. Open champion needed only to play solid serve and
volley tennis to overcome the 23-year-old Popp whose jangling
nerves caused him to make a string of errors including five
doubles faults in his first service game.
</P>
<P>
The towering Popp, who beat current and former French Open
champions Gustavo Kuerten and Michael Chang, in earlier rounds did
show flashes of brilliance on the backhand and he broke Rafter's
serve to force the third set tiebreak.
</P>
<P>
But he could not match Rafter's touch and anticipation,
dropping four of his service games during the match and losing the
tiebreak 7-1.
</P>
<P>
Venus and Serena Williams warmed up for their singles semifinal
by bludgeoning 43-year-old Martina Navratilova and her South
African partner Mariaan de Swardt out of Wimbledon 4-6, 6-2,6-1 in
the women's doubles quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
In a battle of power against precision, the sisters showed no
mercy in the match and ended Navratilova's chances of winning a
record-equalling 20th Wimbledon title.
</P>
<P>
"That was fun," Navratilova said afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Asked if this would be her last Wimbledon, Navratilova, the
holder of 19 Wimbledon titles, said: "I am not sure."
</P>
<P>
Navratilova and her partner Mahesh Bhupathi were knocked out of
the mixed doubles in the first round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
