<HEADLINE> Cook sees British euro membership as "inevitable" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
said on Thursday that Britain's eventual membership of the euro,
the European single currency, was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
As one of Prime Minister Tony Blair most pro-euro ministers,
Cook said Britons could be won over to support it. But he also
made it clear that he was not calling for Britain to join the
single currency immediately.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions at a meeting of pro-European trade
unionists, the foreign secretary said the long term attraction of
the euro appeared irresistible despite widespread public
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
"I welcome the fact that in those opinion polls which show the
majority of the public are against joining the euro, they all show
the same two thirds majority believe joining the euro is
inevitable," a Reuters report quoted Cook as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I think they are right," he said.
</P>
<P>
"That is a powerful factor that will work in our favor over
time," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Blair said earlier last year that his government is united in
favor of joining the euro in principle, provided five economic
conditions are met. If those tests are met it would put the issue
to a referendum after the next general election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
