<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior U.N. Official to Assess Humanitarian Needs in Horn of Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior United Nations
relief officer is on her way to the Horn of Africa to assess the
humanitarian situation there after devastating droughts and armed
conflicts ravaged the region, a U.N. spokesman announced here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Carolyn McAskie, acting Emergency Relief Coordinator, left New
York Wednesday for a 10-day mission during which she will also
review the U.N.'s existing coordination arrangements for meeting
the needs of the affected populations, the spokesman, Manoel de
Almeida e Silva, said.
</P>
<P>
During her trip, McAskie will visit Ethiopia, Eritrea and
Kenya, as well as Burundi, where she will visit "regroupment"
camps of internally displaced persons and discuss with the U.N.
Country Team the implications of the country's peace process for
the humanitarian community.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan dispatched a
reconnaissance mission to Ethiopia and Eritrea in order to devise
plans for a U.N. peacekeeping mission along their bitterly
contested frontier.
</P>
<P>
The mission, headed by Major-General Timothy Ford of Australia,
included military, political, legal and humanitarian experts, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the Security Council, Annan said he was
following up on a cease-fire accord signed by the two Horn of
Africa countries -- Ethiopia and Eritrea -- last month that called
for U.N. peacekeepers to patrol the border.
</P>
<P>
Any troop contingents still have to be approved by the
Security Council, which met on the issues behind closed doors on
Thursday, although members have said they were in favor of the
force, estimated between 2,000 and 4,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea signed the cease-fire pact in Algeria on
June 18 under the auspices of the Organization of African Unity
that ended the fighting. Tens of thousands of people were killed
and more than one million were uprooted from their homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
