<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kenya Takes Measures to Combat Famine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Li Jinqi
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Following the government's decision
to waiver duty of imported maize in mid-June, millers in Kenya
will import 600, 000 tons of maize from South Africa in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
As one of the urgent steps to fight the famine caused by the
worst drought in the past 40 years, Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi announced on June 14 to waiver duty on imported maize to
encourage millers to import more and build up the depleted food
reserve.
</P>
<P>
Tahir Sheikh Said, a leading miller at the Indian Oceanic port
city of Mombasa in southeastern Kenya, expected that the first
consignment of the imported maize would be in the country in
August.
</P>
<P>
Over the past eight years, Kenya has witnessed vicissitudes of
a dry spell in 1992, heavy rains and floods in 1997 and 1998,
followed again by the current dry spell in most parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the prevailing drought, maize production in Nakuru
District in Rift Valley Province, the country's breadbasket in the
central part of Kenya, will drop by 60 percent, from 1.5 million
bags (90 kg per bag) in 1999 to 700,000 bags this year.
</P>
<P>
On June 7, President Moi once again appealed for international
 assistance for emergency food relief for three million Kenyans in
30 districts affected by the severe drought.
</P>
<P>
He said due to circumstances which are beyond the government's
control, Kenya is in the grip of very worrying natural calamities
which include extreme drought conditions and a spreading and
deepening famine.
</P>
<P>
The president estimated that the country required 150 million
U.S. dollars from local and international donors to tackle the
crisis, of which food will take 85 percent, while water and
sanitation among others take the rest.
</P>
<P>
To combat the famine effectively, Moi on June 8 appointed an
11-member crisis committee consisting of cabinet ministers and a
bank governor to coordinate and monitor the distribution of famine
relief food.
</P>
<P>
Moi promised donors that his government would establish more
relief food distribution points and incorporate non-governmental
organizations and U.N. agencies to ensure transparency in aid food
management.
</P>
<P>
A few days later, the Office of the President announced in a
statement that the government has distributed 811,600 bags of
maize to drought and famine-hit areas, leaving only less than
60,000 bags as relief stocks.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Kenyan government has set aside 500 million
shillings (about 6.5 million U.S. dollars) to buy 303,000 bags of
commercial maize which will be converted into relief food for
needy districts.
</P>
<P>
The Relief and Rehabilitation Department under the Office of
the President has also made strong representation to the Treasury
for three to four billion shillings (about 40 to 53 million
dollars) which will cater for purchase of approximately 2.2
million bags of maize for stock reserves.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, government officials at various level have
urged farmers in drought-hit areas to plant more drought-resistant
crops such as cassava, potatoes and bananas as a way of easing the
raging famine menace.
</P>
<P>
President Moi's appeal for emergency food assistance received
timely and positive responses from Italy, Britain, Japan, the
Netherlands and the United States among other countries, as well
as U.N agencies and non- governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government, through its ambassador to Kenya,
pledged to provide 2,555 tons of relief food including wheat and
rice, worth 55 million shillings (about 725,000 dollars) to help
save Kenyans from starvation.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program (WFP) also immediately promised to send
7,273 tons of aid food such as maize, beans and edible oil to
Kenya's Tana River region, one of the country's 18 worst
drought-hit districts.
</P>
<P>
So far, the U.N. agency has assisted a total of 2.7 million
drought- stricken Kenyans at a cost of 43 million dollars, with
emphasis on the 12 worst hunger-hit districts.
</P>
<P>
In order to tackle growing hunger in Kenya, David Fletcher,
WFP's Deputy Country Director for Kenya, on July 5 urgently
appealed for 88 million dollars to feed 3.3 million Kenyans until
the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000706.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quick Step being Urged for Transgenic Food Regulations in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada's provincial agriculture
ministers urged the federal government to move quickly to
establish clear regulations for transgenic foods Thursday in
Fredericton, New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
At the conclusion of the annual meeting of federal and
provincial agriculture ministers, Ontario Agriculture Minister
Ernie Hardeman said that Canadian farmers "are looking for some
direction, as quickly as possible."
</P>
<P>
Hardeman and his counterparts said Canadian farmers are looking
for government to conclude the discussions on labelling so as to
get things done for the production of tansgenic foods, which have
become important cash crops since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Federal Agriculture Minister Lyle Vanclief told the meeting
that discussions on labelling need caution and prudence.
</P>
<P>
"Before you can have any kind of labelling on anything, there
must be a set of criteria that can clearly demonstrate to the
producers that the labelling is credible, meaningful and
enforceable," he explained.
</P>
<P>
He said Canadian farmers are making their own decisions, rather
than waiting for governments to tell them what to do with
engineered products.
</P>
<P>
"Farmers don't just blindly plant. They want to grow what they
can market, not try to market what they grew," he argued.
</P>
<P>
Under a global Biosafety Protocol adopted by more than 130
countries in Montreal in late January this year, a label is
required for transgenic foods indicating that they might be a
product of genetically modified organism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
