<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Denies Allegation at Parliamentary Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, July 6 (Xinhua)-- Former German chancellor Helmut Kohl
Thursday denied the allegation that he had destroyed evidences of
his illegal funding scandal.
</P>
<P>
Appearing at the parliamentary hearing here, Kohl blamed his
successor Gerhard Schroeder for hutching a plot to ruin his fame.
</P>
<P>
"Behind this screenplay is the chancellery. All those things
began after my time," Kohl told the special parliamentary
committee that was investigating his scandal.
</P>
<P>
He rejected the allegation by deputy parliamentary president
Burkhard Hirsch that he should be responsible for the missing
files that might be evidences for his scandal.
</P>
<P>
The Hirsch report said large amount of computer files-equal to
1.2 million pages of paper--in Bonn chancellery had been erased
after Kohl was defeated in the election in September 1998 and
before Schroeder took over the power.
</P>
<P>
Including in the files were records about Germany's sale of
Leuna petroleum complex to France and the armored-vehicle deal
with Saudi Arabia in early 1990s. Kohl and his Christian
Democratic Union (CDU) were suspected to take kickbacks from the
deals.
</P>
<P>
As before, Kohl still refused to point out who had anonymously
donated millions of marks to his CDU, but he said there were not
so many donators as the media had reported, saying, "They are not
a legion."
</P>
<P>
The former chancellor accused German media for "falsification"
in the report on his scandal. He said the ARD and WDR, two
television networks that first covered the illegal donation of CDU
last November, were "incomparably stupid." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
