<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Gives Euro Hints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
Thursday gave his strongest hint yet that he expects to take
Britain into euro, the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
In some of the most pro-euro remarks yet from the British
premier, Blair told BBC television that if the time came he was
prepared to lead from the front in a referendum to ratify a move
to join euro.
</P>
<P>
He said Britain has the lowest inflation in Europe and if it
carries on that way, the euro would be good for the nation.
</P>
<P>
"If we rule out the euro, we're turning our back on the future
of this country," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was clearly trying to clarify his position
as he came under fire from anti-euro audience members during the
BBC Question Time programme.
</P>
<P>
He said he would recommend joining the euro if it was good for
jobs, mortgages and industry, even if it was unpopular.
</P>
<P>
His Labor government's long-standing position is that if five
key economic tests are met, it will hold a referendum and
recommend people vote to join.
</P>
<P>
When asked why Britain would not join the euro immediately,
Blair defended his decision by saying that if Britain joined now
it would be bad for its economy.
</P>
<P>
Blair's government repeatedly said it is united in favor of
joining the euro in principal, providing five economic conditions
are met. If those tests are met it would put the issue to a
referendum after the next election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
