<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Vietnam Resume Talks on Trade Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and Vietnamese trade
negotiators kicked off here Thursday two days of talks aiming to
finalize a historic market-opening pact.
</P>
<P>
During the talks on Thursday and Friday, U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky and Vietnamese Trade Minister
Vu Khoan are expected to hammer out details of the proposed
bilateral trade agreement, a result of four years of on-and-off
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed trade pact, Vietnam would lower its tariffs
and undertake a broad range of measures to open its markets to U.S.
goods, services and investment.
</P>
<P>
In return, Hanoi would get access to the U.S. market under the
same system of low tariffs given to most nations.
</P>
<P>
If agreed, the trade pact would be a milestone in U.S.-Vietnam
relations which was normalized in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
