<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Court Confirms Decision against Volkswagen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Court of First
Instance ruled Thursday that German car maker Volkswagen should be
fined with 90 million euros (86 million U.S. dollars) for its
violation of European Union (EU)'s competition law.
</P>
<P>
The court in a judgement upholds a decision of the European
Commission, the EU's executive body, against Volkswagen
establishing very serious infringement of EU Competition Rules",
the EU Commission said.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive has accused the Volkswagen of preventing its
Italian importer and its dealers in Italy to sell new cars to non-
residents, in particular German and Austrian consumers. Therefore,
the EU decided in early 1998 to fine the German car maker with 102
million euros (97 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In April 1998, Volkswagen appealed against this decision with
the Court of First Instance, by rejecting the Commission's
findings and considering the amount of the fine as totally
inadequate. Now the court in its judgement only slightly revised
the sum of fine to 90 million euros.
</P>
<P>
EU Commissioner Mario Monti said that this ruling is good news
for European consumers. "The possibility to buy goods at better
prices in other member states is indeed one of the key advantages
of the single market," he said.
</P>
<P>
The EU competition commissioner also said the decision adopted
by the European Commission against Volkswagen indicated that it
does not hesitate to take the necessary measures against motor
manufactures who do not comply with the rules on motor vehicle
distribution.
</P>
<P>
According to previous record, the penalty imposed on Volkswagen
is by far the harshest one in the 15-country European Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
